"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643856","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-29","<p>HM Forces Railcard is governed by a contract between the Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC) and the Ministry of Defence. The provision of the railcard is a concession and not a condition of service. The terms and conditions are periodically reviewed by the Department and ATOC, and there are currently no plans to extend the current concession or establish a separate railcard for Service veterans.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","54837","2016-11-29T16:09:18.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643856/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643856/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-24","Railways: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy to establish a separate railcard for armed forces veterans as part of his policy initiatives arising from the Armed Forces Covenant.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","54836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643857","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Ministry of Defence normally pays compensation only where it accepts that it is or might be held legally liable for the harm in question. These payments are distinguished from ex gratia payments, which require the consent of HM Treasury. In the special circumstances of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan HM Treasury authorised the Department to make ex gratia payments in theatre in appropriate circumstances to nationals of those countries who had suffered harm or damage as a result of UK military activities: information on such payments was published annually. No such authorisations are currently in force, and any proposal to make ex gratia compensation payments to civilians killed or injured by UK airstrikes would require HM Treasury approval on an exceptional basis. There are currently no such proposals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-12-02T13:12:17.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643857/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643857/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-24","Ministry of Defence: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his policy is on the issuing of compensation of ex gratia payments to civilians killed or injured by UK airstrikes.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","54689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643858","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-30","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>However, the number of RAF personnel embedded with each nation’s military on Maritime Patrol Aircraft (MPA) duties as part of the Seedcorn Initiative and Exchange Officer programme, on 1 April each year, is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td colspan="4"><p>Number of Personnel Embedded</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>US</p></td><td><p>Canada</p></td><td><p>Australia</p></td><td><p>New Zealand</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The number of RAF personnel who were embedded in each nation’s military on MPAs from 2010 to 2016, who no longer serve in the British Armed Forces, is set out below:</p><p>US 1</p><p>Canada 1</p><p>Australia 0</p><p>New Zealand 1</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","54567 ; 54568 ; 54569","2016-11-30T16:07:48.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643858/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643858/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-24","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many RAF crews have been embedded in the Canadian military on maritime patrol duties in each year since 2010; and how many of those crew members no longer serve in the UK armed forces.","false","Biography information for Sir Gerald Howarth","Aldershot","Sir Gerald Howarth","54682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643859","Department for Education","false","2016-12-09","<p>To ensure that local authorities were fully funded to implement the Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) reforms, the Government provided them with a £70million SEND Reform Grant in 2014-15, aimed at helping them to prepare for their new statutory duties. Newham Borough Council’s share of this grant amounted to £693,476.</p><p> </p><p>Through the ‘SEND Implementation Grant’, additional implementation funding of £45.2million was provided in 2014-15; £31.7million was provided in 2015-16 and £35.8million was provided in 2016-17. Newham Borough Council’s shares of these allocations were £350,763 in 2014-15; £255,814 in 2015-16 and £291,459 in 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to direct implementation funding for local authorities, the Government has provided:</p><p> </p><ul><li>£45million between 2014-15 and 2016-17 for Independent Supporters to help parents and young people through the process of education, health and care assessment and planning;</li><li>£5million for local authorities to increase opportunities for work experience and supported internships in 2015-16;</li><li>£6.75million between 2014-15 and 2016-17 to provide grant support for every Parent Carer Forum in England;</li><li>funding for a network of nine lead authorities in 2015-16 and 2016-17 to coordinate peer support; and</li><li>funding for a delivery consortium of voluntary and community sector organisations providing specialist advice and support to local authorities and their partners.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Government has also committed to funding the SEND Implementation Grant, Independent Supporters and Parent Carer Forums for 2017-2018.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-12-09T16:14:42.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643859/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643859/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Special Educational Needs: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that Newham Borough Council is fully funded to implement the Government's educational reforms on provision for children and young people with special needs; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","54671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643860","Department for Education","false","2016-12-01","<p>We have provided local authorities with the operational information on revenue funding for 2017-18 which includes the removal of the Education Services Grant. We intend to lay draft regulations to effect these arrangements in legislation as soon as possible in the new year.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-01T15:18:00.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643860/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643860/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to bring forward the legislative proposals that will be required as a consequence of the planned removal of the Education Services Grant to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","54716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643861","Department for Education","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Government believes that every child should experience a high quality arts education throughout their time at school. All schools, including academies and free schools, must provide a broad and balanced curriculum that promotes the spiritual, moral, cultural, mental and physical development of pupils at the school.</p><p> </p><p>The National Curriculum, which includes music, art and design, drama, and dance, is compulsory for maintained schools. Academies and free schools are not required to teach the National Curriculum, but can use it as a benchmark.</p><p> </p><p>Last month, we announced a multimillion pound investment in music and cultural education. This includes:</p><ul><li>£300 million over the next four years for a network of music education hubs</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>£29 million a year until 2018 for the Music and Dance scheme which provides support for talented young musicians and dancers to attend world-class institutions</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>£4.1 million a year until 2018 for cultural education programmes</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>£500,000 a year until 2018 for In Harmony, an orchestral training programme for pupils in disadvantaged areas</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>£600,000 for other small music programmes across the country for each year until 2020</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>£13.5 million a year until 2018 for the Dance and Drama Awards Scheme. This scheme offers income-assessed support for tuition fees and living costs for students aged 16-23 at a number of high quality private dance and drama schools</li></ul>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-01T15:21:49.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643861/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643861/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Arts: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to promote arts subjects in schools.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","54740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643862","Department for Education","false","2016-11-29","<p>We do not hold this information. Ofsted inspectors make graded judgements on the effectiveness of leadership and management; the quality of teaching, learning and assessment; pupils’ personal development, behaviour and welfare; and pupils’ outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>In making these judgements, inspectors will evaluate the experience of particular individuals and groups, including those with medical needs, and this will inform the overall judgment of the school. These evaluations may not always be visible in the report, as Ofsted inspectors will be careful not to identify individual pupils.</p><p> </p><p>We know how important it is that children with medical conditions are supported to enjoy a full education. That is why in 2014 we introduced a new duty to require governing bodies to make arrangements to support pupils with medical conditions and have provided statutory guidance outlining schools’ responsibilities in this area.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work with organisations with experience in supporting children with medical conditions to help raise awareness of the duty.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-11-29T17:41:58.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643862/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643862/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Pupils: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many schools have been judged by Ofsted to not provide the necessary level of support to children with medical conditions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","54885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643863","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>The replacement of the buildings at Whitehaven Academy has previously been considered through capital bids to the Priority Schools Building Programme (PSBP), which were unsuccessful.</p><p> </p><p>The £4.4 billion PSBP programme is intended to replace or refurbish those school blocks in the worst condition across the country. By focusing on those individual buildings in the worst condition, we are targeting limited funding in the most effective way possible and securing best value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>DfE officials visited the school in April and October 2016 to help identify priority condition issues and gave advice to the Bright Tribe Trust as to how they should focus investment using funding from the annual school condition allocation that the Bright Tribe Trust receives.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-08T17:46:17.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643863/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643863/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Whitehaven Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will provide funding for the rebuilding of the Whitehaven Academy.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","54886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643864","Department for Education","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Department has never used a workforce supply model for early years initial teacher training, and as a consequence did not define a need for new entrants in 2016/17. We have an ambition to grow the number of graduates who are entering the early years teaching profession, and make places available to meet the demand from the market.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-29T17:30:28.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643864/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643864/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her Department's target number for new entrants to early years initial teacher training programme has been for each academic year since that programme was established; and what that target is for each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","54831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643865","Department for Education","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Head of Profession for Statistics for the Department is currently reviewing the data collected on early years initial teacher training. The first stage of our review into early years data has focussed on the entrants into early years initial teacher training and we are pleased to have published statistics for these in this year’s initial teacher training census. The second stage of our review is focussing on outcomes, such as completion rates. We are unable to provide any data while this review is ongoing - but we will be publishing information on this in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-29T17:29:57.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643865/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643865/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many new entrants of the early years initial teacher training programme received a bursary and subsequently withdrew or failed to complete the course in each year since that programme was established.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","54830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643866","Department for Education","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Government is determined to build a country that works for everyone. We welcome Sir Nick Weller’s independent report which identifies the need to increase the supply of high-quality teachers and senior leaders in the North, the limited capacity of multi-academy trusts (MATs), and the need for more schools to offer a stretching curriculum, as key challenges in the north.</p><p> </p><p>The report highlights the need for all schools to be funded fairly and according to their circumstances. That is why we are introducing a national funding formula, which will allocate funding to schools according to actual measures of schools’ and pupils’ needs.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this year we held the first stage of consultation on our proposals to introduce national funding formulae for schools and high needs. The first stage of consultation invited responses on the principles, architecture and the building blocks we proposed to include in the national funding formulae.</p><p> </p><p>We will issue our response to the first stage consultation on the national funding formula, confirming which factors will be included, and launch the second stage of the consultation, later this year. The second stage will invite responses on the weightings we propose to give each of the factors in the formulae, and provide illustrative allocations for schools and local areas.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-01T15:19:05.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643866/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643866/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Schools: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Northern Powerhouse Schools Strategy, published on 23 November 2016, what estimate she has made of the level of underfunding of schools in the north of England.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","54788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643867","Department for Education","false","2016-12-01","<p>In Key Stages 3 to 4 in state funded secondary schools, the proportion of mathematics hours taught by a teacher with a relevant post A-level qualification was 82.0% in the 2015/16 academic year.</p><p> </p><p>A full breakdown of the qualification types is included in Table 12 in the statistical first release ‘School Workforce in England, November 2015’, which was published in June 2016: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Information for Key Stages 1 and 2 is not available as we do not collect information on mathematics teaching time in primary school through the school workforce census.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-01T15:20:06.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643867/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643867/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Mathematics: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of mathematics teachers who teach pupils at key stage (a) 1, (b) 2, (c) 3 and (d) 4 have a mathematics degree.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","54841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643868","Department for Education","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Head of Profession for Statistics for the Department is currently reviewing the data collected on early years initial teacher training. The first stage of our review into early years data has focussed on the entrants into early years initial teacher training and we are pleased to have published statistics for these in this year’s initial teacher training census. The second stage of our review is focussing on outcomes, such as completion rates. We are unable to provide any data while this review is ongoing - but we will be publishing information on this in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-29T17:31:15.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643868/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643868/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many entrants to the early years initial teacher training programme received a government bursary of what amount in each year since 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","54828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643869","Department for Education","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Head of Profession for Statistics for the Department is currently reviewing the data collected on early years initial teacher training. The first stage of our review into early years data has focussed on the entrants into early years initial teacher training and we are pleased to have published statistics for these in this year’s initial teacher training census. The second stage of our review is focussing on outcomes, such as completion rates. We are unable to provide any data while this review is ongoing - but we will be publishing information on this in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-29T17:30:52.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643869/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643869/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many entrants to the early years initial teacher training programme have (a) completed, (b) withdrawn from and (c) failed to finish that programme in (i) 2013-14, (ii) 2015-16 and (iii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","54829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643870","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-29","<p>The table below summarises Government capital spend on flood and coastal risk management schemes in Cumbria for each year between April 2007 and March 2016. These investments included funding for flood alleviation schemes in Carlisle, completed in 2010 at a cost of £22.5 million, and Penrith, costing £5.6 million and completed in 2011. Flood alleviation schemes in Keswick and Cockermouth were also completed in 2012 and 2013 at a cost of £6 million and £4.4 million respectively.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Government capital investment for Cumbria (in £m)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>8.314</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>11.354</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>12.483</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>9.507</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>6.328</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>4.291</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2.394</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2.086</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2.502</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency does not retain historic spend data prior to 2007 which can be split by specific geographic regions consistently. This is due to different financial accounting systems being in place prior to 2007</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-29T12:17:02.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643870/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643870/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Flood Control: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much has been spent from the public purse on flood (a) defence and (b) prevention schemes in Cumbria in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","54825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643871","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-29","<p>The RPA said it would investigate BPS 2015 claims where there is a discrepancy between the claim information and that held on the Rural Payments Service through a planned reconciliation process. This started after the BPS 2016 application window and looked at an initial stock of 13,607 claims for England. The agency continues to review new queries as they arise.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-29T15:45:36.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643871/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643871/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many farmers have been underpaid under the 2015 Basic Payments Scheme.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","54834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643872","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-29","<p>Three schemes will benefit from the £20 million of new flood defence investment announced in the Autumn Statement 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The schemes are as follows;</p><ul><li>Burton Upon Trent Flood Alleviation Scheme,</li><li>Otley Flood Alleviation Scheme; and</li><li>Stainforth Dunston Hill Flood Alleviation Works.</li></ul><p> </p><p>In total the schemes will better protect 5,000 properties (4,100 home and 900 non-residential properties).</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-29T10:58:53.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643872/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643872/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Flood Control: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to paragraph 3.25 of the Autumn Statement 2016, which schemes will receive the £20 million of investment in new flood defences.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","54833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643873","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-29","<p>Blue Flag is an international award certified by the Foundation for Environmental Education and is independent of the UK Government and the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has made clear that we will keep working to improve our environment and make sure it is protected for future generations.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-29T13:25:37.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643873/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643873/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Beaches: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her plans are for replacing the EU Blue Flag Scheme to ensure the cleanliness of beaches, protection of wildlife and the enforcement of sea regulations after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","54862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643874","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>These are the figures currently available for annual testing in England for the three areas:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Edge</p></td><td><p>High Risk</p></td><td><p>Low Risk</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2016 to 20 Oct 2016</p></td><td><p>£745,617</p></td><td><p>£1,261,432</p></td><td><p>£15,928</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2015 to March 2016</p></td><td><p>£1,169,118</p></td><td><p>£2,001,883</p></td><td><p>£35,589</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The total does not include any testing undertaken by Official Veterinarians in the first few months of year 2015-2016. Testing prior to year 2015-2016 is not available at the moment as the Veterinary Delivery Partners only started operating in May 2015. The testing undertaken by Official Veterinarians up to a point in 2015 is not readily available.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-08T16:59:58.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643874/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643874/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Cattle: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much the Government spent on annual testing of cattle in the high risk, edge and low risk areas in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643875","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-01","<p>Data for the previous 12 months is not readily available due to a change in the way this data is recorded in April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Removal times for the period April 2016 to November 2016 -</p><p> </p><p>a) Average number of days = 9.3</p><p>b) Minimum number of days = 0</p><p>c) Maximum number of days = 89 days (as a result of farmer refusal to allow removal and bankruptcy complications).</p><p> </p><p>These figures include animals slaughtered on farm for welfare or other reasons and those for which there was a delay in removal for any reason including to allow for calving, medicine withdrawal.</p><p> </p><p>These figures cover England, Scotland and Wales.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-01T12:32:23.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643875/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643875/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the (a) average, (b) minimum and (c) longest time between an animal testing positive for TB at a farm test and being collected from that farm for destruction has been in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643876","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-01","<p>There are a total of six abattoirs contracted by the Animal and Plant Health Agency to accept TB reactor cattle – five in England, one in Wales. There is also an abattoir in Scotland that routinely takes reactors from farms in Scotland for the Animal and Plant Health Agency. However owners can choose to privately slaughter any reactor animal under a private arrangement with a slaughterhouse of their choice, which may or may not be one of these seven abattoirs.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-01T12:35:28.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643876/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643876/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many abattoirs in the UK process TB reactor cattle.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643877","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-02","<p>The additional funding announced in the Budget 2016 has enabled the Environment Agency to progress 16 flood risk management schemes. All of these were in the early stages of development requiring funding certainty to progress further. The additional funding has ensured no further contributions are required and enabled the design to commence.</p><p> </p><p>Of these, one scheme, the Calder Valley Flood Risk Reduction Scheme has already started construction. The remaining schemes are in the design stages and the Environment Agency expect construction to start shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The schemes progressed by the additional funding will better protect at least 7,500 homes from flooding when completed.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-02T12:33:08.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643877/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643877/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on how many of the flood defence and prevention schemes that were announced in Budget 2016 construction has begun.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","54898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643878","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-01","<p>There are a total of 6 abattoirs contracted by Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) to accept TB reactor cattle – 5 in England, 1 in Wales. There is also an abattoir in Scotland that routinely takes reactors from farms in Scotland for the Animal and Plant Health Agency. All of these received reactor cattle in 2016. Other abattoirs would have been used to slaughter reactors under a private arrangement with the owner. The Animal and Plant Health Agency does not have a list detailing abattoirs that processed reactors under a private arrangement with the owner.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-01T12:48:07.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643878/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643878/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many abattoirs in the UK processed TB reactor cattle in 2016.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643879","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>There are seven premises that are contracted by the Animal and Plant Health Agency to slaughter TB reactor cattle.</p><p> </p><p>Between 1 November 2015 and 31 October 2016 36,689 TB reactor cattle were slaughtered in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>A producer can choose to send cattle to a non-contracted approved slaughterhouse. Between 1 November 2015 and 31 October 2016, 230 TB reactor cattle were slaughtered in non-contracted TB reactor slaughterhouses in England and Wales.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T13:46:13.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643879/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643879/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many TB reactor cattle were taken to each abattoir in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643880","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>It is a condition of approval that all slaughterhouses are required to have adequate lairage facilities and there is no distinction between requirements for day or night time lairage.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently 180 approved cattle slaughterhouses in England and Wales (some of these premises also slaughter other species).</p><p> </p><p>Regulation 853/2004, Annex III, Section I, Chapter II, sets out the requirements for slaughterhouse lairage and states:</p><p> </p><p>- Adequate and hygienic lairage facilities must be equipped for watering the animals and, if necessary, feeding them.</p><p> </p><p>Animal welfare standards are set out in Regulation 1099/2009 on the protection of animals at the time of killing. Annex III states:</p><p> </p><p>- Animals which have not been slaughtered within 12 hours of their arrival must be fed, and subsequently given moderate amounts of food at appropriate intervals (usually every 12 hours). In such cases, the animals shall be provided an appropriate amount of bedding or equivalent material which guarantees a level of comfort appropriate to the species and the number of animals concerned. This material shall guarantee an efficient drainage or ensure adequate absorption of urine and faeces.</p><p>- Arrangements must be made for milking dairy animals at intervals of not more than 12 hours.</p><p>- Animals which are not taken directly to the place of slaughter after being unloaded must have drinking water available to them from appropriate facilities at all times.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T13:49:53.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643880/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643880/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Slaughterhouses: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many abattoirs have adequate lairage for cattle kept overnight.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643881","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>The animal welfare standards for TB reactor cattle kept overnight are the same as for any other cattle sent to slaughter for human consumption.</p><p> </p><p>These standards are available in Regulation 1099/2009 on the protection of animals at the time of killing. Annex III of the Regulation states:</p><p> </p><p>- Animals which have not been slaughtered within 12 hours of their arrival must be fed, and subsequently given moderate amounts of food at appropriate intervals (usually every 12 hours). In such cases, the animals shall be provided an appropriate amount of bedding or equivalent material which guarantees a level of comfort appropriate to the species and the number of animals concerned. This material shall guarantee an efficient drainage or ensure adequate absorption of urine and faeces.</p><p>- Arrangements must be made for milking dairy animals at intervals of not more than 12 hours.</p><p>- Animals which are not taken directly to the place of slaughter after being unloaded must have drinking water available to them from appropriate facilities at all times.</p><p> </p><p>Regulation 853/2004, Annex III, Section I, Chapter II, regarding the requirements for slaughterhouses, also states for lairages that:</p><p> </p><p>- Adequate and hygienic lairage facilities must be equipped for watering the animals and, if necessary, feeding them.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T13:47:04.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643881/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643881/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the Government's welfare standards are for adequate lairage for TB reactor cattle which are kept overnight.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643882","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-01","<p>The furthest journey recorded in the last three years was agreed for six cattle, in December 2015.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>a) The estimated journey time was 4.5 hours.</p><p> </p><p>b) The furthest reported distance travelled by a reactor in the last 3 years is 260 miles.</p><p> </p><p>This was agreed as the nearest contracted abattoirs were unable to take the reactors within the ten working day target for removal.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-01T12:29:51.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643882/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643882/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the furthest distance is in (a) time and (b) mileage that a TB reactor cow has travelled to a UK abattoir which processed TB reactor cattle in the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643883","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-29","<p>Defra received £8.8m in 2015/16 in salvage receipts for TB reactor cattle.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-29T14:03:13.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643883/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643883/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the annual value is, excluding testing costs on farm or in a laboratory, of TB reactor salvage to the Government.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643884","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Food Standards Agency does not routinely record this information however it is usual industry practice that TB reactor animals are slaughtered on the same day of arrival at the abattoir.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T13:50:59.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643884/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643884/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the longest time is that a TB reactor cow has spent in lairage before its destruction.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643885","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-02","<p>The cost for using the six contracted abattoirs for reactor removal is calculated per mile and this varies depending on the number of animals in the batch.</p><p> </p><p>The maximum distance travelled would generally be 199 miles.</p><p> </p><p>If travelling 199 miles:</p><ul><li>1-5 animals would cost £407.95.</li><li>6-10 animals would cost £489.54</li><li>11-17 animals would cost £561.18</li><li>17+ animals would cost £610.93</li></ul>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-02T13:51:38.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643885/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643885/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the total cost of transport and lairage is for TB reactor cattle travelling the furthest distance.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","54746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643886","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-01","<p>£20m was announced in the Autumn Statement for capital flood defences to better protect over 5,000 homes. The three schemes to receive this funding are in Yorkshire and Staffordshire.</p><p> </p><p>£150m of funding was also announced to improve the resilience of roads and rail infrastructure in areas that experienced severe flooding last winter. The Department for Transport will announce further details of the investment in due course.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-01T12:26:29.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643886/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643886/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Flood Control: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to paragraph 3.25 of the Autumn Statement 2016, which flood defence schemes in Lancashire have been granted funding.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","54667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643887","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-01","<p>The 25 year environment plan will be developed in two stages. Firstly, a consultative Green Paper which will be published soon and secondly, the full plan itself. We will use feedback from the Green Paper to help inform the plan.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-01T17:49:32.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643887/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643887/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-24","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether mechanisms to reducing the UK's international footprint outside the UK and in the UK's Overseas Territories will be included in her Department's planned 25 year environment plan.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","54668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643888","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>Female Genital Mutilation is a high priority for the UK and we will continue to work with governments and partners to end the abusive practice. DFID leads our international efforts on FGM and it is raised by our Heads of Missions, officials and visiting Ministers. We will continue to do this, including in the countries raised.</p><p>We also work closely with international partners, including the EU and UN, especially in countries where we do not have an Embassy, to press governments to prevent FGM. Supported by UK funding, the UN Joint Programme on FGM and cutting has led coordinated efforts to influence national policy and legislation in 17 high prevalence countries.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","54938 ; 54939 ; 54940 ; 54942 ; 54943 ; 54944 ; 54945 ; 54946 ; 54947 ; 54948 ; 54950","2016-12-01T14:35:01.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643888/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643888/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Djibouti: Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 23 November 2016 to Question 52971, if he will instruct the UK Ambassador with responsibility for Djibouti to make representations on the practice of female genital mutilation to the government of Djibouti.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","54686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643889","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-30","<p>​I understand Maria Chin Abdullah has now been released following her detention under the Special Offences (Security Measures) Act 2012 (SOSMA). This is a positive development. We have a regular dialogue with Malaysian ministers on human rights, including the use of SOSMA and the right to peaceful protest. Officials from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in London also meet periodically with representatives of Malaysian Civil Society to hear their concerns. We shall continue to follow these issues and wider civil society in Malaysia very closely.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-11-30T16:22:21.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643889/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643889/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Malaysia: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Malaysian counterpart on the (a) use of the Security Offences (Special Measures) Act 2012 in that country to arrest and detain Maria Chin Abdullah and other peaceful demonstrators and campaigners and (b) release of those demonstrators detained under that Act.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","54680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643890","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>No official structural surveys have been made of the manmade structures on the Outer Islands. However a British patrol regularly checks these islands. Guidance for visiting yachtspeople makes clear that these structures are unsound and are out of bounds. Those who enter the structures do so at their own risk. Fines are issued to those who are caught damaging buildings.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-02T14:41:34.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643890/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643890/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","British Indian Ocean Territory: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the Government last made an assessment of the safety and stability of manmade structures of the outer islands of the British Indian Ocean Territory; and when the Government next plans to make such an assessment.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","54666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643891","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>Definitive numbers are not available.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-02T14:44:24.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643891/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643891/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","British Indian Ocean Territory: Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many customers have used the British Indian Ocean Territories post office (a) in person and (b) online in each year for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","54665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643892","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We continue to raise our concerns about the trial of members of the human rights NGO TRACKs directly with the Sudanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs as part of our ongoing human rights dialogue, most recently during the visit of the Sudanese Undersecretary for Foreign Affairs on 10 October. I also made our wider human rights concerns clear to the Sudanese delegation during the same visit.</p><p>In coordination with our international partners we have ensured that there is a diplomatic presence at each stage of the trial of the members and affiliates of the Centre for Training and Human Development. Officials from our Embassy last attended on 30 August, and US officials attended the most recent hearing on 22 November.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-01T14:16:30.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643892/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643892/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Sudan: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Sudanese counterpart on the trial of members and affiliates of the Centre for Training and Human Development.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","54661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643893","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We continue to raise our concerns about the trial of members of the human rights NGO TRACKs directly with the Sudanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs as part of our ongoing human rights dialogue, most recently during the visit of the Sudanese Undersecretary for Foreign Affairs on 10 October. I also made our wider human rights concerns clear to the Sudanese delegation during the same visit.</p><p>In coordination with our international partners we have ensured that there is a diplomatic presence at each stage of the trial of the members and affiliates of the Centre for Training and Human Development. Officials from our Embassy last attended on 30 August, and US officials attended the most recent hearing on 22 November.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-01T14:18:40.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643893/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643893/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Sudan: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the fairness of the trial relating to members and affiliates of the Centre for Training and Human Development in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","54662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643894","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We continue to raise our concerns about the trial of members of the human rights NGO TRACKs directly with the Sudanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs as part of our ongoing human rights dialogue, most recently during the visit of the Sudanese Undersecretary for Foreign Affairs on 10 October. I also made our wider human rights concerns clear to the Sudanese delegation during the same visit.</p><p>In coordination with our international partners we have ensured that there is a diplomatic presence at each stage of the trial of the members and affiliates of the Centre for Training and Human Development. Officials from our Embassy last attended on 30 August, and US officials attended the most recent hearing on 22 November.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-01T14:21:37.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643894/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643894/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Sudan: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Sudanese counterpart on the six-month detention of Khalafalla Al-Afif Mukhtar, Midhat Afif Al-Deen Hamdan and Mustafa Adam on charges relating to their work and affiliation with the Centre for Training and Human Development.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","54663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643895","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>The British Indian Ocean (BIOT) Post Office on Diego Garcia is managed and run by Sure, the on-island telecoms provider through a contract with the BIOT Administration. The Post Office is located in a building owned and managed by Sure.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-02T14:55:58.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643895/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643895/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","British Indian Ocean Territory: Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what arrangements are in place for the ownership and management of the British Indian Ocean Territories post office.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","54664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643896","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>​I met State Counsellor Daw Aung San Suu Kyi in London on 13 September together with the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May), where we discussed ways in which the UK could support Burma's political transition including the promotion of human rights and protection of minorities. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Boris Johnson) also discussed the transition with her on 12 September during the same visit. In addition, the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November and met a number of Government Ministers to discuss human rights, democracy and the protection of minorities. I plan to visit to Burma in 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-01T15:54:12.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643896/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643896/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans he has to visit Burma to discuss the (a) promotion of human rights, (b) strengthening of democratic process and (c) protection of ethnic, religious and sexual minorities.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643897","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>The British Government is deeply concerned by the recent flare-up of violence in Rakhine State. This was triggered on 9 October, when three Burmese Border Guard Police posts were attacked by armed Rohingya groups. We have called for restraint, humanitarian access and an investigation. We are aware of a number of disturbing reports of human rights violations by security forces in Rakhine State. We have made several representations to the Government of Burma, both through our Ambassador and also through Ministerial contacts. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November. She urged Burmese Government Ministers to resume immediate humanitarian access to the affected areas in Northern Rakhine and for a full and independent investigation into all reports of human rights violations. The Government of Burma has committed publicly to do so. I also raised the situation in Rakhine with the Burmese Minister of Construction in London on 29 November.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-01T15:33:45.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643897/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643897/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security and human rights situation in Rakhine, Burma.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643898","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>I have not met President Htin Kyaw. However, I did meet State Counsellor Daw Aung San Suu Kyi in London on 13 September together with the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Theresa May), where we discussed ways in which the UK could support Burma's political transition. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Boris Johnson) also met her on 12 September where he too discussed the transition. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November and met a number of Government Ministers. The British Embassy in Rangoon, including the British Ambassador, regularly discuss democratic transition with Members of Parliament from the National League of Democracy. The UK has been a leading supporter of Burma's reform process since 2011. We supported elections in 2015 which led to Burma's first civilian Government in over half a century. However, the transition is not complete and we will continue to work with the new Government to consolidate the reforms. This includes a package of support worth £113 million this year.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-01T16:14:40.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643898/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643898/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with (a) his Burmese counterpart, (b) Htin Kyaw, (c) elected officials of the National League for Democracy and (d) Aung San Suu Kyi on transitioning from the former military government to the current government in that country.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643899","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>The British Government is deeply concerned by the recent flare-up of violence in Rakhine State. This was triggered on 9 October, when three Burmese Border Guard Police posts were attacked by armed Rohingya groups. We have called for restraint, humanitarian access and an investigation. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November. She urged Burmese Government Ministers to resume immediate humanitarian access to the affected areas in Northern Rakhine and for a full and independent investigation into all reports of human rights violations. The Government of Burma has committed publicly to do so. I also raised the situation in Rakhine State with the Burmese Minister of Construction in London on 29 November.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-01T15:55:41.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643899/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643899/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Burmese counterpart on the recently reported attacks on (a) Yekai Chaung Gwasone, (b) Dar Gyi Sar and (c) Myaw Taung.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643900","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government works regularly with the US on a whole range of energy issues and will continue to do so. My Hon Friend, the Minister of State for Climate Change and Industry (Nick Hurd) discussed this issue with the US Energy Secretary, Ernest Moritz, during the UN Climate Change Conference in Marrakesh earlier this month.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-11-29T17:57:01.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643900/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643900/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","USA: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his US counterpart on international co-operation to tackle climate change.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643901","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), discussed international climate change matters with the Minister of State for Climate Change and Industry, my Hon. Friend the Member for Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner, in October and corresponded on the Government’s approach ahead of the recent UN Climate Conference in Marrakesh. In recent months, Ministers from the two Departments have also discussed cross-government programmes related to international climate objectives.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-11-29T17:44:12.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643901/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643901/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643901/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Minister of State for Climate Change and Industry on the Government's approach to tackling climate change.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643902","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>The only private visitors to the British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT) are yachtspeople who stop off in the Outer Islands of the Territory if they have been granted a permit. The masters of vessels which have been issued mooring permits are expected to provide daily updates to British Forces HQ on their position whilst in the waters of the Territory and to ensure compliance with all conditions attached to the permission to enter the Territory. These waters are regularly patrolled and monitored by Visiting Vessels Control Officers and other authorised persons, who are empowered to take all necessary action against those who breach any condition imposed by a mooring permit, or who otherwise act in a way that is contrary to the law.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-02T14:56:43.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643902/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643902/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","British Indian Ocean Territory: Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department takes to monitor the (a) number and (b) behaviour of private visitors to the British Indian Ocean territory.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","54702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643903","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>The British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT) is not a tourist destination and permits to moor in the Outer Islands of BIOT are only issued where this is necessary to facilitate a vessel's safe passage across the Indian Ocean. Laws specifically enabling the Administration of BIOT to issue mooring permits (or the equivalent) were introduced in December 1993, but records of the total number of such permits issued only go back to 2004. The following numbers have been recorded: 2004 - 2; 2005 - 3; 2006 - 4; 2007 - 40; 2008 - 68; 2009 - 82; 2010 - 99; 2011 - 42; 2012 - 41; 2013 - 27; 2014 - 36; 2015 - 51; 2016 - 17 (to date).</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-02T14:54:02.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643903/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643903/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643903/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","British Indian Ocean Territory: Sailing Boats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, for how many years the Government has been issuing mooring permits for yachts visiting the British Indian Ocean territory; and how many such permits have been issued in each year for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","54701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643904","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>Climate change is one of the important global issues that the Foreign and Commonwealth Office works on through diplomacy around the world. Following entry into force of the Paris Agreement, UK climate diplomacy is focussed on ensuring its full implementation and effective follow up, and maximising the commercial opportunities for British business that a global transition to a low-carbon economy affords. We are therefore exploring options for senior representation on climate change to ensure the UK remains at the forefront of international efforts.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-11-29T17:43:02.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643904/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643904/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","UK Special Representative for Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to retain the role of Special Representative for Climate Change within his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643905","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Foreign Secretary is considering options for the Special Representative on Climate Change. An announcement will be made in due course.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-11-29T17:41:25.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643905/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643905/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","UK Special Representative for Climate Change: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he plans to appoint a new Special Representative for Climate Change.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643906","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>​I refer the Hon. Lady to the answer I gave in the House to my Hon. Friend the Member for Harrow East (Bob Blackman MP) on 22 November <em>Official Report</em>, Column 750. It is for the Indian Government and the Reserve Bank of India to define what is Indian legal tender. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has updated its travel advice, advising British nationals travelling to India how to act in this matter, and we advise those nationals to monitor the situation closely. The Reserve Bank of India has currency controls in place which limit the amount of rupees (INR25,000) that can be brought into India by overseas residents.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-01T16:12:54.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643906/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643906/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","India: Bank Notes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Indian government on ensuring that demonetised 500 and 1,000 rupee notes can be exchanged in the UK before the end of 2016.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","54889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643907","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not provide combat training to the Burmese military. We do provide educational training to the Burmese military in the form of programmes delivered by the Defence Academy of the United Kingdom on the role of the military in a democracy, leadership and English language training. The British Government does not hold information on whether any Burmese Army soldiers who have received educational training from the UK are involved in military operations against the Rohingya in Rakhine State, nor have we undertaken any evaluation of how educational training provided to the Burmese military has led to improvements in human rights. Our programme of engagement with the Burmese military remains under continual review.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","54867 ; 54868","2016-11-29T16:15:53.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643907/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643907/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-24","Burma: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has undertaken any evaluation of how training the Burmese military has led to improvements in human rights.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","54899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643908","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>We are aware of a number of disturbing reports of sexual violence against Rohingya women by security forces in Rakhine State. These were alleged to have taken place during the ongoing security operations in Rakhine, triggered on 9 October when three Burmese Border Guard Police posts were attacked by armed Rohingya groups. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November. She urged Burmese Government Ministers to resume immediate humanitarian access to the affected areas in Northern Rakhine and for a full and independent investigation into all reports of human rights violations. The Government of Burma has committed publicly to do so. I also raised the situation in Rakhine State with the Burmese Minister of Construction in London on 29 November.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-01T15:32:08.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643908/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643908/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the alleged incident of rape of Rohingya women by security forces in Rakhine State, Burma, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","54815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643909","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>​We have raised the situation in Rakhine with the Government of Burma, including with State Counsellor Daw Aung San Suu Kyi as well as the Ministers for Defence, Home Affairs, Border Affairs, Immigration, and Information.</p><p>The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November. She urged Burmese Government Ministers to resume immediate humanitarian access to the affected areas in Northern Rakhine and for a full and independent investigation into all reports of human rights violations. The Government of Burma has committed publicly to do so. We have also raised the importance of access and freedom for media personnel in Burma.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-11-29T17:45:26.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643909/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643909/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has raised with Burma State Counsellor Daw Aung San Suu Kyi  (a) the banning of media from areas of Rakhine State, (b) government blocking of humanitarian aid to Rohingya in Rakhine State and (c) the sacking of Myanmar Times journalist Fiona MacGregor for reporting on the mass rape of ethnic Rohingya women.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","54864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643910","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not provide combat training to the Burmese military. We do provide educational training to the Burmese military in the form of programmes delivered by the Defence Academy of the United Kingdom on the role of the military in a democracy, leadership and English language training. The British Government does not hold information on whether any Burmese Army soldiers who have received educational training from the UK are involved in military operations against the Rohingya in Rakhine State, nor have we undertaken any evaluation of how educational training provided to the Burmese military has led to improvements in human rights. Our programme of engagement with the Burmese military remains under continual review.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","54868 ; 54899","2016-11-29T16:15:53.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643910/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643910/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-24","Burma: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has undertaken a review of offering further training to the Burmese military to take account of recent serious human rights violations by the Burmese military against Rohingya civilians in Rakhine State and against ethnic Kachin civilians in Kachin State and northern Shan State, Burma.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","54867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643911","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not provide combat training to the Burmese military. We do provide educational training to the Burmese military in the form of programmes delivered by the Defence Academy of the United Kingdom on the role of the military in a democracy, leadership and English language training. The British Government does not hold information on whether any Burmese Army soldiers who have received educational training from the UK are involved in military operations against the Rohingya in Rakhine State, nor have we undertaken any evaluation of how educational training provided to the Burmese military has led to improvements in human rights. Our programme of engagement with the Burmese military remains under continual review.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","54867 ; 54899","2016-11-29T16:15:53.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643911/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643911/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-24","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on whether any Burmese Army soldiers who have received training from the UK are involved in military operations against the Rohingya in Rakhine State.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","54868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643912","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>​Egypt is one of the FCO's 30 Human Rights Priority Countries. In the FCO's Human Rights and Democracy Report published in April, we raised concerns about the detention of journalists and restrictions on freedom of expression in Egypt. FCO ministers and officials regularly raise human rights concerns with the Egyptian authorities, including the detention of journalists. For example, we raised the arrests of journalists Amr Badr and Mohamed el Sakka in May with the Egyptian Ambassador to London.</p><p>The UK has also raised its concerns about human rights in Egypt at the UN, most recently at the Human Rights Council in September. We also supported an EU statement at the same session which specifically expressed concerns about the arrests of journalists in Egypt. When the Prime Minister met President Sisi in September, she noted the importance of human rights. The UK wants to see more political progress and better protection of human rights in Egypt. That includes implementation of the rights guaranteed by Egypt's constitution, more freedom of expression, and more space for NGOs and civil society. These rights and freedoms are key for Egypt's long-term stability and we will continue to raise our concerns with the Egyptian authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-01T14:38:23.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643912/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643912/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Egypt: Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Egypt on the imprisonment of journalists and curtailment of the free press in that country.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","54851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643913","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>We continue to follow developments in Turkey closely and underline the importance of the rule of law and the protection of freedom of expression.</p><p>I raised these issues during my visit to Turkey on 19 October, and most recently with Turkey's Minister for Europe, Omer Celik, in a phone call on 7 November. HMG also regularly discusses such issues in international fora.</p><p>The EU issued a statement on 8 November expressing concern at recent events in Turkey, including the detention of MPs.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-02T14:43:45.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643913/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643913/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Turkey: Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Turkey on the imprisonment of journalists and curtailment of the free press in that country.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","54852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643914","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>DFID Parliamentary Under Secretary of State Mr Wharton visited the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) on the 18-20 November. He met the Prime Minister, the Minister for Interior/Security, the main opposition leader, the speaker of the lower house of Parliament and leader of President Kabila's political grouping. Mr Wharton discussed elections with all interlocutors and pressed them to show the flexibility necessary to reach an inclusive deal on timely elections and transition.</p><p>I visited the DRC in August where I discussed elections with the DRC government and pressed them to make more progress towards holding timely elections. I also met opposition figures, and emphasised the importance of elections to the DRC's continuing development. The embassy in Kinshasa maintains a regular dialogue with the Government of the DRC about the postponement of the elections to April 2018.</p><p>EU funding for elections is dependent on the DRC government meeting conditions set out in UN Security Council resolution 2277. The conditions include a transparent election process based on an inclusive political agreement and a clear timetable approved by stakeholders. We are working closely with EU partners in support of this.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-29T17:45:55.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643914/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643914/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Democratic Republic of Congo: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the decision by President Kabila of the Democratic Republic of Congo to delay elections due to take place in November 2016 until April 2018; and whether he has made an assessment of the adequacy of the funding made available by the EU for those elections.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","54774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643915","Department of Health","false","2016-11-29","<p>Non-European Economic Area (EEA) migrants coming to the United Kingdom for more than six months pay a health surcharge as part of their visa application fee, before being able to access National Health Service care. They will be issued with Biometric Residence Permits which can be presented to indicate entitlement to free care.</p><p>Visitors from the EEA are asked to bring a valid European Health Insurance Card which will cover them for treatment that becomes necessary during a visit to the UK until their planned return.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance to NHS trusts advises them on asking the right questions to establish their patients’ eligibility to free healthcare. We have also developed a system whereby a patient’s chargeable status, once this is known, is flagged on the patient’s summary care record so that others within the NHS with the appropriate accreditation can see this information. This makes the process of assessing patient’s eligibility simpler and more effective.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-29T13:54:30.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643915/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643915/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will assess the potential merits of issuing qualifying patients with medical identification cards as part of his Department's policy on health tourism; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","54780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643916","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has advised that it defines medical technologies as all products, except medicines, used in healthcare to diagnose, prevent, monitor or treat illness or disability, for example a pacemaker, knee replacement, X-ray machine or blood pressure monitor.</p><p> </p><p>NICE has advised that its Technology Appraisal Committee has appraised seven such medical technologies in the last five years. A further four technologies have guidance currently in development.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T14:45:21.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643916/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643916/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Medical Treatments: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will estimate how many proposals for new medical technologies the NICE Technology Appraisal Committee has discussed in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","54777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643917","Department of Health","false","2016-11-30","<p>Social care is a means tested service. The Care Act 2014 requires that local authorities must assess any adult who appears to have a care and support need. Where a person has needs which do not meet the national eligibility criteria, as set out in the Care Act, their local authority must provide the person with information and advice on what support is available in the community to meet those needs.</p><p> </p><p>The Autumn 2015 Spending Review announced that local authorities who are responsible for social care would have the ability to raise additional funding to spend exclusively on adult social care. If all local authorities use this to its maximum effect it could raise nearly £2 billion a year by 2019-20. 95% of local authorities have taken up the precept in 2016-17, raising £382 million extra for social care this year, in line with the Office for Budget Responsibility forecast. In addition from 2017 the Spending Review made available new funds for social care services, rising to £1.5 billion by 2019-20. This will be made available to local authorities directly and is to be included in an improved Better Care Fund.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","54790","2016-11-30T14:48:39.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643917/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643917/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643917/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the number of people requiring social care who do not receive such care.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","54787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643918","Department of Health","false","2016-11-30","<p>Social care is a means tested service. The Care Act 2014 requires that local authorities must assess any adult who appears to have a care and support need. Where a person has needs which do not meet the national eligibility criteria, as set out in the Care Act, their local authority must provide the person with information and advice on what support is available in the community to meet those needs.</p><p> </p><p>The Autumn 2015 Spending Review announced that local authorities who are responsible for social care would have the ability to raise additional funding to spend exclusively on adult social care. If all local authorities use this to its maximum effect it could raise nearly £2 billion a year by 2019-20. 95% of local authorities have taken up the precept in 2016-17, raising £382 million extra for social care this year, in line with the Office for Budget Responsibility forecast. In addition from 2017 the Spending Review made available new funds for social care services, rising to £1.5 billion by 2019-20. This will be made available to local authorities directly and is to be included in an improved Better Care Fund.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","54787","2016-11-30T14:48:39.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643918/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643918/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Local Government Association press release, entitled £2.6 billion could be needed to fix social care, published on 13 October 2016, what steps he is taking to reduce the funding gap in social care.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","54790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643919","Department of Health","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Department holds no specific information on Prevention of Future Deaths reports issued to National Health Service trusts. The Department is aware only of those Prevention of Future Deaths Reports that are sent to it by Coroners.</p><p> </p><p>Prevention of Future Deaths reports and responses are published by the Chief Coroner at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/about-the-judiciary/office-chief-coroner/pfd-reports" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/about-the-judiciary/office-chief-coroner/pfd-reports</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-29T09:02:15.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643919/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643919/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Patients: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on future death reports that have been issued in relation to NHS trusts in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","54875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643920","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>We have made no such assessment. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) and NHS England are consulting on the proposals and they are therefore subject to change. NICE and NHS England will assess the impact of the proposals in light of consultation responses.</p><p> </p><p>Independent evidence suggests that the most important attraction for companies to invest in research in the United Kingdom is the availability of world-class scientific expertise, which is the focus of the Government’s effort to ensure the UK remains at the forefront of global research and development.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T15:01:09.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643920/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643920/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Life Sciences: Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the proposals for changes to the arrangements for evaluating and funding drugs and other health technologies appraised through NICE's technology appraisal and highly specialised programmes, published on 13 October 2016, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of proposals for the introduction of a budget impact threshold on the level of inward investment into the UK life sciences sector.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","54855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643921","Department of Health","false","2016-11-29","<p>Initial contact with the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme involves some form of assessment, before a patient enters treatment, in conjunction with discussion between the patient presenting and the Psychological Wellbeing Practitioner or High Intensity Therapist in order to design an effective treatment programme and agree interventions.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-29T14:34:36.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643921/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643921/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many referrals to the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme ended after (a) entering treatment and (b) completing treatment without receiving an assessment in each clinical commissioning group in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","54877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643922","Department of Health","false","2016-11-29","<p>Information on the number of people prescribed a particular treatment or the medical condition treated is not collected centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-29T14:31:43.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643922/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643922/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Vitamin B12","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were prescribed vitamin B12 treatment for a mental health condition in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","54878"
