cretary of State for Justice, if she will take steps to support an inquiry by Hull City Council into the loss of the ashes of Louise Medlam's daughter, Chloe, in 1996.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","54802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643979","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Secretary of State recently met Diana Johnson MP and her constituent Tina Trowhill whose Action for Ashes Hull organisation represents parents in Hull. The Secretary of State expressed her deepest sympathy for all the parents who had not had their infants’ ashes returned to them after cremation and explained the government’s position.</p><p> </p><p>The government is supportive of local investigations into historic infant cremation practices but does not plan to order such inquiries in Hull or elsewhere. Our clear priority since we received the Emstrey report in June 2015 has been to put measures in place across England and Wales to prevent such distressing infant cremation practice ever happening again. That is why we held a consultation which closed in March, announced our proposals in light of consultation responses in July, introduced a new statutory definition of ashes in October and have put in place a National Cremation Working Group of experts which is now advising us on more complex regulations and new statutory forms which will come into effect in 2017. The Working Group, which includes Action for Ashes Hull, will also assist us in developing new codes of practice, training and information for bereaved families.</p><p> </p><p>Hull City Council has assured us that it has provided the information that it holds to all bereaved parents who have approached it about their babies’ cremations. This includes Jenni Murray, Angela Hughes and Louise Walker.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","54799 ; 54801 ; 54802 ; 54803 ; 54804 ; 54805 ; 54806 ; 54807","2016-12-02T11:51:23.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643979/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643979/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-24","Cremation: Babies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will take steps to support an inquiry by Hull City Council into the loss of the ashes of Angela Hughes' son, Reece, in 1996.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","54800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643980","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>My Department is working closely with other departments across Whitehall, in particular the Department for Exiting the European Union, as well as with the Northern Ireland Executive to ensure that Northern Ireland’s needs and interests are taken into account in preparing for the UK’s exit from the EU. The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-12-06T12:20:37.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643980/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643980/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-24","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many projects in operation in his Department are related to the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643981","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>I recognise the benefits of the all-island energy market to Northern Ireland. Security of supply both to domestic consumers of gas and electricity, as well as business and agriculture is vitally important.</p><p> </p><p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, Lord Dunlop, has met with industry representatives as part of the round of Business Advisory Group meetings, and I have spoken to senior industry representatives and Northern Ireland Executive ministers to hear first-hand the range of issues that generators face.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains supportive of the proposed new developments, as well as the move to the Integrated Single Electricity Market.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","54718","2016-12-05T16:11:54.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643981/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643981/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-24","Energy Supply: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment his Department has made of the potential benefits to Northern Ireland energy consumers of maintaining an all-island single electricity market and arrangements for gas.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","54719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643982","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>I recognise the benefits of the all-island energy market to Northern Ireland. Security of supply both to domestic consumers of gas and electricity, as well as business and agriculture is vitally important.</p><p> </p><p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, Lord Dunlop, has met with industry representatives as part of the round of Business Advisory Group meetings, and I have spoken to senior industry representatives and Northern Ireland Executive ministers to hear first-hand the range of issues that generators face.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains supportive of the proposed new developments, as well as the move to the Integrated Single Electricity Market.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","54719","2016-12-05T16:11:54.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643982/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643982/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-24","Energy Supply: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps his Department is taking to maintain security of supply for consumers in Northern Ireland by retaining the ability to access and trade with European electricity and gas markets.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","54718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643983","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-28","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe. Cabinet Office will work together with the Department for Exiting the EU (DExEU) and other departments to deliver this. The Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU exit. Cabinet Office is working closely with DExEU to ensure that the full range of opportunities is identified, and risks mitigated across areas of Cabinet Office responsibility.</p><p>The Cabinet Office exists to support the Prime Minister and ensure the effective running of government. We are also the corporate headquarters for government, in partnership with HM Treasury, and we take the lead in certain critical policy areas. As a result, rather than having stand-alone projects related to the UK’s exit from the EU, all aspects of Cabinet Office responsibility are now adapting to the current context, which includes preparing for the UK’s exit from the EU.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","53886","2016-11-28T10:02:41.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643983/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643983/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-24","Prime Minister: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many projects in operation in 10 Downing Street are related to the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643984","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-30","<p>The Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU Exit.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe, and departments will work together to deliver this.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-30T15:27:01.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643984/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643984/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-11-24","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many projects in operation in his Department are related to the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643985","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe, and departments will work together to deliver this. The Department for Transport is contributing to this effort. Current work is not project-based.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-01T13:39:47.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643985/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643985/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many projects in operation in his Department are related to the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643986","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Department for Transport has been participating in negotiations on the revision of the European Aviation Safety Agency’s (EASA) Basic Regulation, which will include EU-wide safety rules for all unmanned aircraft.</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Aviation Authority participates in the EASA Expert Group of subject matter experts, and will assist with the development of the Implementing Rules that sit beneath the Basic Regulation.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-01T13:36:21.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643986/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643986/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 27 April 2016 to Question 34680, what his Department's current involvement is with the European Aviation Safety Agency's development of EU-wide safety rules for drones.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","54690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643987","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Department for Transport and the Civil Aviation Authority work with a wide range of partners, including the British Airline Pilots' Association and the Police, to ensure our understanding of potential hazards to aircraft remains up to date. Work is underway to better understand the risk posed by drones to commercial aircraft and ensure that the regulatory and industry responses remain fit for purpose.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-01T12:15:48.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643987/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643987/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with (a) the British Airline Pilots' Association, (b) the Civil Aviation Authority, (c) the Metropolitan Police and (d) other relevant stakeholders on the near-miss incident between a drone and a passenger plane on 18 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","54775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643988","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-29","<p>I have asked Highways England to look at shortening the length of roadworks to reduce the impact on road users. Following my discussions with them, Highways England are working towards utilising shorter lengths and looking at whether they can safely increase speed limits through roadworks, which will improve the overall customer experience and minimise disruption.</p><p> </p><p>Contraflows (utilising the opposite carriageway) and reducing lane size can be used to allow for more lanes to be opened during maintenance and other works on a motorway and the UK guidance on roadworks layouts is contained within the Traffic Signs Manual Chapter 8.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England are currently testing running traffic through roadworks at 60mph whilst they undertake technology commissioning on a future smart motorway scheme on M1 J34-35a near Sheffield in South Yorkshire.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-29T16:36:48.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643988/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643988/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Motorways: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with Highways England on its policy of contraflow and reducing lane size during maintenance or other work on motorways; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","54779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643989","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Autumn Statement on 23 November 2016 announced £100 million would be made available from 2017/18 to improve resilience to flooding on our road network. The Department for Transport will now develop criteria to be published in due course for which local highway authorities can submit bids to the Department.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-29T16:54:51.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643989/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643989/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Roads: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 3.25 of the Autumn Statement 2016, on which schemes the £100 million of investment in road resilience projects referred to will be spent.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","54832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643990","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-01","<p>The main elements in the cost-benefit analysis that Highways England are conducting on alternative proposals for the A27 road in and around Worthing, are the: a) costs (constructions costs, land costs, preparation costs, supervision costs, maintenance costs), b) benefits (travel time, vehicle operating costs, accidents impacts, construction delay, maintenance delay, changes in indirect taxation, reliability) and c) environmental impacts, such as CO2 emissions, air quality, noise, etc.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-01T11:58:45.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643990/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643990/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","A27: Worthing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the main elements are in the cost-benefit analysis conducted on alternative proposals for the A27 road in and around Worthing.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","54798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643991","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-01","<p>I understand that the conclusion of the Inspector’s report would not have been placed online as a matter of course back in 1996/97. Highways England will investigate to see if the document is still held. If it is located and it is still relevant, then it will be published on the A27 road project website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-01T11:55:16.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643991/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643991/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","A27: Worthing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make available online the 1996-97 conclusions of the inspector's report stemming from the inquiry on the A27 road proposals for Worthing and District.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","54797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643992","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Secretary of State for Transport announced on 17 November an additional £10m funding to help strengthen the resilience of the railway line from Exeter to Newton Abbot via Dawlish. In addition, we have asked Network Rail to develop schemes to improve the resilience of the rail network to flooding in the Axe Valley (Devon) and around the River Irwell in Manchester. The Department will continue to discuss with Network Rail other priorities for investment to improve resilience.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-29T16:51:51.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643992/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643992/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Railways: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 4.8 of the Autumn Statement 2016, which projects will receive funding for rail resilience.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","54881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643993","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-01","<p>The evidence from the trial indicates that longer semi-trailers are principally being used on major motorway and trunk routes between depots and warehouses. There is a general evaluation of the trial, involving the collection of extensive data on safety, environmental impact and economics of longer semi-trailers. The results, published on the Department for Transport website, include a significant reduction in the number of journeys required compared to the use of standard length semi-trailers.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-01T12:30:41.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643993/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643993/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","Large Goods Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the longer semi-trailer trial on residents in small villages.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","54861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643994","Wales Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU Exit. The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe, and departments will work together to deliver this.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-12-01T12:56:12.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643994/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643994/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-11-24","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many projects in operation in his Department are related to the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643995","Wales Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Departmental spend on agency workers is set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Spend £</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>11,378</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>32,047</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>36,603</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>38,903</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>114,023</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>258,545</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>56,561</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The expenditure on agency costs increased in 2013/14 and 2014/15 because of the need to fill at short notice a number of business critical posts temporarily whilst recruitment campaigns were underway.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-11-29T17:30:06.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643995/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643995/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-11-24","Wales Office: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much his Department has spent on agency staff in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","54763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643996","Wales Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>There are six staff in the Office of the Secretary of State for Wales working in a press or communications role, supporting three Ministers. Their respective civil service (CS) grades are shown below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>CS Grade</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No. of staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SCS Pay Band 1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grade 7</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Senior Information Officer (SIO)</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Information Officer (IO)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-11-29T17:35:29.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643996/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643996/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-11-24","Wales Office: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff of his Department at each civil service grade are employed in a press or communications role.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","54765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643997","Wales Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>There are six staff working in the communications department of the Office of the Secretary of State for Wales supporting its three Ministers, five of whom deal with press matters as part of their broader remits.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-11-29T17:32:05.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643997/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643997/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-11-24","Wales Office: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff of his Department are employed in its (a) press and (b) communications department.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","54766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643998","Wales Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>Work relating to exiting the EU forms part of the policy portfolio of most Wales Office staff.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-11-29T17:54:56.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643998/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643998/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-11-24","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many full-time equivalent civil servants in his Department are working exclusively on issues arising as a result of the UK voting to leave the EU; and what the civil service grade is of each of those officials.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","54764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643999","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU Exit. My Department, working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union, is undertaking a variety of analytical and organisational work to understand the impacts of leaving the EU across its entire policy remit. My Department is also making sure that the implications of leaving the EU are understood and accounted for within the context of pre-existing projects. The Government is united in its ambition to deliver a successful withdrawal from the EU and a new relationship with Europe, and departments will work together to deliver this.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-12-01T15:40:36.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643999/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643999/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-11-24","Government Equalities Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many projects in operation in her Department are related to the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644000","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>The impact that a carer’s earnings, including those receiving the National Minimum Wage, will have on their entitlement to Carer’s Allowance (CA) will depend on the number of hours they work a week and their net salary for CA purposes once allowable deductions have been made.</p><p> </p><p>The CA earnings limit will be increasing from £110 to £116 a week from April 2017. This 5% increase outstrips the current average increase in earnings. Up to 2,000 carers will benefit from this change.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-29T13:03:25.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644000/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644000/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Carer's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people will lose entitlement to carer's allowance as a result of increases to the national minimum wage taking their income over the earning limit for that allowance.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","54762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644001","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-30","<p>The Prime Minister has instructed all departments to identify potential opportunities that will arise in their areas from EU Exit. Officials in the department are engaging with teams in the Department for Exiting the European Union to consider the implications of exiting the EU on DWP projects and policy objectives.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-11-30T15:37:21.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644001/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644001/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many projects in operation in his Department are related to the UK's exit of the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","54750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644002","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-02","<p>As of June 2016 there were 1,930 parents with care and 2,150 non-resident parents with a Child Support Agency case in the Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ol><li>Figures rounded to the nearest 10.</li><li>Cases have been allocated to a parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care or non-resident parent for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems and cases managed off system to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</li></ol>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-02T12:38:10.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644002/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644002/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) parents with care and (b) non-resident parents there are in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency with a Child Support Agency case.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644003","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-02","<p><strong>Child Support Agency</strong></p><p> </p><p>a) As at June 2016 the total value of arrears on cases in the Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency stood at £5.30m.</p><p>b) As at June 2016 the total value of arrears on cases in Scotland stood at £280.11m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Child Maintenance Service</strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on geographical breakdowns on the Child Maintenance Service is not routinely recorded for management information purposes and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>1) Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10,000.</p><p>2) Cases have been allocated to a parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care or non-resident parent for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems and cases managed off system to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-02T12:46:32.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644003/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644003/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the total amount of child maintenance arrears is in (a) Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency and (b) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644004","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>We have seven older claimant champions across the jobcentre network, one operating in each of the GB regions. These were introduced in April 2015 to increase awareness among Work Coaches of the barriers faced by older claimants. The Champions work collaboratively with 34 District Leads, along with other colleagues, to raise the profile of older claimants at an operational level, highlight the benefits of employing older people and provide advice and best practice to share nationally.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","54708","2016-11-29T16:03:49.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644004/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644004/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Jobcentres: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many older people champions are employed in job centres.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","54707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644005","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>We have seven older claimant champions across the jobcentre network, one operating in each of the GB regions. These were introduced in April 2015 to increase awareness among Work Coaches of the barriers faced by older claimants. The Champions work collaboratively with 34 District Leads, along with other colleagues, to raise the profile of older claimants at an operational level, highlight the benefits of employing older people and provide advice and best practice to share nationally.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","54707","2016-11-29T16:03:49.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644005/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644005/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Jobcentres: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the role is of older people champions in job centres.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","54708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644006","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of customers using the services of food banks and is therefore unable to provide an estimate.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-02T13:08:03.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644006/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644006/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to make an estimate of the number of customers of his Department in Scotland who are using the services of food banks.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644007","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Departmental Annual Report for 2015/2016 includes the final outturn numbers for Employment Programmes from 2011/12 to 2015/16 (page 123 of the report), which includes Work Choice.</p><p> </p><p>The annual spend on Work Choice for the years requested is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Amount £m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>124</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>88</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>79</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-29T13:13:31.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644007/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644007/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Employment Schemes: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much was spent from the public purse through the Work Choice programme on employment support in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","54673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644008","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Work, Health and Disability Green Paper, published last month, launched the Department’s consultation so we can listen to disabled people, their families and friends, service providers, employers, and anyone else who wants to see change. Proposals focus on changes that can be made to the welfare system, by employers and across health services to ensure that the health needs and employment aspirations of disabled people and people with long-term health conditions are better supported. The Department is not looking at implementing specific policies during the consultation period, other than the ones specifically announced in the Green Paper.</p><p> </p><p>At Spending Review 2015, we announced a real terms increase in investment in employment support for disabled people and people with health conditions. As part of this real terms increase in investment, the Green Paper provided additional detail on the practical support to be made available for claimants with limited capability for work from April 2017, rising from £60m in 2017/19 to £100m in 2020/21.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-02T13:04:17.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644008/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644008/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Employment and Support Allowance: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Welfare Reform of 27 January 2016, Official Report, HL1315, on the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, whether he plans for spending on employment support for disabled people to be greater or less after the implementation of the policies in his Department's recent Green Paper on work, health and disability.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","54866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644009","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Child Maintenance System offers choice to all parents, so that those who can collaborate and manage their maintenance arrangements themselves are helped to do so through Direct Pay and those who cannot, have access to the statutory service through the Collect and Pay service. In circumstances where on-going maintenance arrangements break down we work with parents to re-establish payments in order to get money to children quicker.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure parents fulfil their financial responsibilities towards their children we have at our disposal a range of strong enforcement powers which we are continually reviewing and looking to improve. We are currently reviewing our arrears and compliance strategy, and will undertake a public consultation on a proposed new strategy in 2017.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-02T12:55:55.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644009/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644009/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to improve the child maintenance system to ensure payments due are received.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","54863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644010","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>The £60 - £100 million per year is additional funding that will deliver a broad range of employment and health support. This will be in tandem with the change to the ESA Work-Related Activity Component and UC Limited Capability for Work element. As set out in the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper some of it will be used to fund additional places on Work Choice and the Work and Health Programme when it is launched.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-29T13:18:22.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644010/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644010/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Welfare Reform and Work Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the oral contribution by the Minister of State for Welfare Reform of  27 January 2016, in the House of Lords, Official Report, column 1315, on the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, whether the £60 to £100 million per year proposed under his Department's Green Paper on work, health and disability to be spent on supporting employment and support allowance claimants into work is in addition to or instead of funding currently being spent in the Work Programme and in Work Choice.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","54869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644011","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>Since it was established in 2012, the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission, now the Social Mobility Commission, has been supported by a Secretariat with a headcount limit of seven FTE civil servants.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-08T17:44:27.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644011/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644011/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Social Mobility Commission: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many full-time equivalent staff worked in the Social Mobility Commission in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","54870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644012","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-02","<p>As of June 2016 there were 1,340 arrears only cases and 430 arrears cases involving current liability in the Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency held by the Child Support Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1) Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10.</p><p>2) Cases have been allocated to a parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care or non-resident parent for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems and cases managed off system to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</p><p>3) A case is classed as having a ‘Current Liability’ if it is open, has children of a qualifying age and has a positive liability (i.e. assessment to pay maintenance). This includes cases due to pay via Maintenance Direct.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-02T12:33:51.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644012/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644012/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Child Support Agency (a) arrears-only and (b) arrears cases involving a current liability for a child there are in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644013","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>We remain committed to ensuring that people have the best support possible to move closer to the labour market and, when they are ready, into work. The change to the ESA work-related activity component will only apply to new claims. There will be no cash losers among those who are already in receipt of ESA and we aim to protect existing ESA claimants who temporarily leave the benefit to try out work and then return to ESA. We will bring forward draft regulations in due course setting out the detail.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-29T17:40:35.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644013/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644013/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-24","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the oral contribution of the Minister for Disabled People, Health and Work of 17 November 2016, Official Report, columns 462 to 464, whether the hardship fund, flexible support fund and other third-party deals will compensate new claimants in full for the loss of the work-related activity group payments.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","54827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644014","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>British Business Bank (BBB) equity programmes have invested over £37m in life science businesses since BBB became a PLC in November 2014. The BBB also manages a number of government programmes which were facilitating finance to businesses prior to November 2014. Including these, BBB equity programmes are currently investing over £130m of finance in life science businesses. Approximately 8% of the BBB’s total equity investment portfolio is invested in life science businesses.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","54848","2016-12-01T11:08:04.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644014/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644014/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","British Business Bank: Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of the British Business Bank's investment portfolio is invested in life science businesses.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","54813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644015","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>The location and provision of its post offices branches is the responsibility of Post Office Limited.</p><p> </p><p>I have asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the Hon Member on this matter and provide the information requested. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","54761","2016-11-29T15:20:50.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644015/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644015/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Post Offices: Off-licences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many post office branches are located in off-licences; where each of those branches is located; and on what date each of those branches was opened.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","54795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644016","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Pubs Code took effect on 21 July 2016 and regulates the relationship between tied pub tenants in England and Wales and the six pub-owning companies which operate 500 or more tied pubs.</p><p> </p><p>We estimate that approximately 11,500 tied pub tenants are covered by the Code.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-29T15:27:02.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644016/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644016/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Public Houses: Tenants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of pub tenants are protected pub tenants.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","54778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644017","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-12","<p>The process for granting Petroleum Exploration and Development Licences is independent from the development of Local Plans.</p><p>The Oil and Gas Authority is the petroleum licensing authority. When approving licences the Oil and Gas Authority considers the applicant’s technical competence and financial viability. Once an area is licensed, oil and gas exploration and drilling are subject to landowner consent, local planning permission and other permits. Planning law requires that applications for planning permission must be determined in accordance with the local authority development plan, unless material considerations indicate otherwise. The process for granting Petroleum Exploration and Development Licences is independent of the development of Local Plans.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-12T11:26:31.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644017/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644017/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Oil: Exploration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Petroleum Exploration and Development Licences have been granted where the Local Plan does not include development land for such purposes.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","54856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644018","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC’s) Employment Status and Intermediaries Team focuses on employment status and employment intermediary risks. Where companies are believed to have misclassified individuals as self-employed, HMRC establishes the facts of the case and will take steps to ensure that all the appropriate tax, National Insurance contributions, interest and penalties are paid.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government announced at Autumn Statement 2016 that, following consultation, it would reforms the intermediaries legislation (commonly known as IR35) to improve the compliance of those working off-payroll through Personal Service Companies in the public sector.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-12-02T13:25:38.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644018/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644018/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Self-employed: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to tackle bogus self-employment.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","54857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644019","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-02","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State wrote to the right hon. Member for Delyn on 28 November.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-02T13:45:46.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644019/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644019/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to his oral contribution of 8 November 2016, Official Report, column 1395, on the Royal Bank of Scotland, when he plans to write to the right hon. Member for Delyn.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","54814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644020","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>British Business Bank (BBB) equity programmes have invested over £37m in life science businesses since BBB became a PLC in November 2014. The BBB also manages a number of government programmes which were facilitating finance to businesses prior to November 2014. Including these, BBB equity programmes are currently investing over £130m of finance in life science businesses. Approximately 8% of the BBB’s total equity investment portfolio is invested in life science businesses.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","54813","2016-12-01T11:08:04.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644020/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644020/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","British Business Bank: Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much the British Business Bank has invested in life science businesses since it was established.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","54848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644021","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-02","<p>The stocking of Fairtrade products and the adoption of Fairtrade principles by retailers are commercial matters for the companies concerned.</p><p>The Government is committed to supporting Fairtrade around the world. Over the last six years, the Department for International Development (DFID) has provided £18m to Fairtrade International to support their work and strengthen the global Fairtrade system. This includes Fairtrade producer and worker organizations that are the drivers of inclusive economic, environmental and social development in their communities around the world. DFID continues to actively engage with Fairtrade on a variety of projects and campaigns, such as the upcoming Fairtrade Fortnight.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-02T14:11:59.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644021/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644021/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Fairtrade Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps he has taken to encourage retailers to stock more Fairtrade products and adopt Fairtrade principles.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644022","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-05","<p>The good work towards a National Innovation Plan will now feed into the broader development of the Industrial Strategy. First and foremost we need long term productivity growth and we must therefore encourage and spread innovation. Science and Innovation is one of our national strengths and will feature strongly in our Industrial Strategy.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-05T10:25:19.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644022/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644022/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644022/answer/previousversion/23429","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the oral contribution by his predecessor of 28 June 2016, Official Report, column 130, when the Government plans to publish a National Innovation Plan.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","54709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644023","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>Since 2015, Government has spent approximately £11 million on a range of carbon capture projects supporting research and development in CO<sub>2</sub> storage, carbon capture technologies and CCS feasibility studies.</p><p>The Department has also commissioned research into the potential of carbon capture and utilisation in the UK and the next generation UK based carbon capture technologies. These will complete in 2017. Additionally, the Government Energy Entrepreneurs Fund has funded approximately £1.6 million in support to innovative carbon capture technologies.</p><p>Phase 5 of this Fund opened on 30 October 2016. This is an additional £9 million of funding which is available for CCS innovation projects. Further information can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-entrepreneurs-fund-phase-5" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-entrepreneurs-fund-phase-5</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-29T16:41:11.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644023/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644023/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what research the Government is conducting on carbon capture and the energy-making process.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","54710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644024","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>There is no EU patent, so patents can only be granted with effect in individual states, either by applying directly to the relevant national office, or through the European Patent Office, which is not an EU body. These will therefore not be affected by the UK leaving the EU. Patents owned by UK businesses with effect in the UK will continue to be governed by national law.</p><p>In contrast, the EU trade mark is a unitary right with effect in the whole of the EU. When the UK leaves the European Union, EU trade marks will still be available to UK business and existing EU trade marks will continue to offer protection in other Member States. We are consulting businesses and considering how existing EU trade marks can continue to provide protection in the UK.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-01T16:23:07.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644024/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644024/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government plans to take to ensure the continued recognition of UK firms' existing trademarks and patents in the EU after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644025","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>The British Business Bank currently facilitates around £310m of finance in Scotland. This includes over £300,000 in loans to 54 start-up businesses in the Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency. Since it was established in 2007, Innovate UK has supported 5 Small &amp; Medium sized Enterprises in the constituency with more than £2.5m in grants. This includes funding two micro enterprises with innovation vouchers in 2013 and 2014. In 2015/16, Innovate UK committed to invest £58.3m in 291 innovation projects in Scotland.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-01T15:53:40.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644025/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644025/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Small Businesses: Rutherglen and Hamilton West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support micro enterprises in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644026","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>The location and provision of its post offices branches is the responsibility of Post Office Limited.</p><p> </p><p>I have asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the Hon Member on this matter and provide the information requested. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","54795","2016-11-29T15:20:50.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644026/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644026/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many post offices are in Bargain Booze shops; where each of those post offices are located; and in what branches was each of those post offices has opened.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","54761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644027","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-05","<p>The proportion of household expenditure spent on energy bills is not available at a regional level. On average, in the UK in 2014, 4.9% of all household expenditure was spent on energy bills. This data is from the Living Costs and Food Survey by ONS and has been calculated by summing the domestic household expenditure on gas, electricity and other household fuels, divided by the total household expenditure.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-05T13:51:30.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644027/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644027/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Energy: Rutherglen and Hamilton West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the average proportion of household expenditure on energy bills was in Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644028","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer I gave her on 2nd November 2016 to Question UIN 50945:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-28/50945/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-28/50945/</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-29T09:32:59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644028/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644028/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on the potential effect of the Government's policy on fracking on local communities.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","54711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644029","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-02","<p>HMG funds a number of organisations, including NERC funded centres and the Met Office Hadley Centre, which are world-leaders in climate research and are active in Arctic research; this includes the monitoring of Arctic temperatures and understanding the reasons for observed changes in temperature.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-12-02T14:05:46.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644029/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644029/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Arctic: Temperature","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if his Department will commission research on the reasons for the unseasonably high temperatures being recorded in the Arctic.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644030","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-29","<p>As part of the National Productivity Investment Fund, the Chancellor of the Exchequer has provided £4,745m of new funding for Research and Development between 2017-18 and 2020-21. This includes a new Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund to direct some of that investment to a number of priority technologies. Further details of the funding will be set out in due course.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-29T15:28:28.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644030/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644030/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the total value is of the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","54712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644031","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Dowling Review has been very influential upon Government thinking. For example, it has guided our approach to establishing UK Research and Innovation to make the science, research and innovation landscape more strategic, coherent and effective. The Government set out an initial response to the Review in the 2016 higher education White Paper and is developing a more detailed response, incorporating the recent Autumn Statement announcements on research and development.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-06T16:50:15.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644031/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644031/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644031/answer/previousversion/23430","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-24","Business-University Research Collaborations Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Answer of 7 December 2015 to Question 18473, whether the Government plans to publish a response to the Dowling Review of Business-University Research Collaborations.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","54729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644032","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>The UK and Australia have a strong trade relationship, with more than £8 billion in UK exports to Australia in 2015. We have established a UK-Australia Trade Working Group to develop this relationship further and start discussions on the option of a future ambitious and comprehensive UK-Australia Free Trade Agreement. The UK has not made assessments at this stage about any external proposals for a specific type of future agreement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:38:32.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644032/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644032/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Trade Agreements: Australia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of potential merits of the proposal by Tony Abbot for a free trade deal between the UK and Australia that abolishes tariffs and quotas on all goods, gives mutual recognition of industry standards and qualifications and allows people to move freely between the two countries.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644033","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Government continues to undertake a range of analyses to inform the UK’s position for the upcoming EU exit negotiations. We are seeking the best possible arrangement for trade in goods and services and the work being conducted reflects this.</p><p> </p><p>The UK’s future relationship with the EU will be contingent on the exit negotiations and the Government will not provide a running commentary on these negotiations.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","54967","2016-12-02T11:11:19.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644033/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644033/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Balance of Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has commissioned cost-benefit analysis of the potential effect of the UK leaving the single market and the customs union on the UK's balance of trade.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644034","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Government will in due course consider all options in the design and content of future bilateral trade agreements. Until the UK leaves the EU, we will remain subject to EU trade agreements and trade policy.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:39:46.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644034/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644034/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what plans the Government has to embed the precautionary principle in UK domestic law as a basis for future bilateral trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644035","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-28","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising for our aviation industry from the UK’s exit from the EU, including the implications for the continued participation in the European Aviation Safety Agency system. Until we leave, EU law will continue to apply to the UK, alongside national rules.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-28T16:32:26.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644035/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644035/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-24","European Aviation Safety Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to maintain the UK's participation in the European Air Safety Agency's work on certifying aircraft, aircraft engines and other related products for safety to exports after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644036","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>My noble Friend the Minister of State for Trade Policy (Lord Price) visited Mexico in April 2016 and met with the President, the Finance Secretary, the Secretary for the Economy, the Minister of State for Trade Policy and the Chief Executive of the state oil company Pemex, who has a seat in Cabinet.</p><p>Earlier this month he visited Mexico again meeting with the Secretary for the Economy, the Minister of State for Trade Policy and the Deputy Foreign Minister.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T17:43:24.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644036/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644036/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Mexico","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what meetings he and Ministers of his Department have had with members of the Mexican government in (a) Mexico and (b) London in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","54706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644037","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>My noble Friend the Minister of State for Trade Policy (Lord Price) recently visited Mexico to discuss the UK-Mexico trading relationship. Officials are exploring how best to ensure continuity for businesses as the UK leaves the EU, and we are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T17:51:24.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644037/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644037/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Trade Agreements: Mexico","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what preparation work is being conducted on negotiating a trade deal with Mexico after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","54705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644038","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>We have a close working relationship with the Mexican Government and are working to increase bilateral trade. During the State Visit to the UK by President Enrique Peña Nieto in March 2015 we held the first meeting of the UK/Mexico Senior Business Leaders Group. In the last year we have made use of ministerial visits to Mexico to promote trade interests including visits by my noble Friend the Minister of State for International Trade Lord Price and ministers from across Government . The DIT team in Mexico are working on 10 High Value Campaigns for exports, and attracting Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) into the UK and ensure that British companies benefit from commercial opportunities.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T17:41:21.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644038/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644038/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Overseas Trade: Mexico","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps the Government is taking to increase trade with Mexico.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","54704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644039","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>These calculations were based on the economic and statistical analysis of market trends, along with information from industry and the Department for International Trade’s global network which identified opportunities for each market. This was also based on the predicted outcomes of ongoing market access work which will generate new opportunities.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-29T15:16:12.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644039/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644039/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Food: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to his Department's press release entitled, Global ambitions for British food and drink could boost economy by nearly £3 billion, if he will publish the methodology used to calculate that the International Action Plan for Food and Drink could benefit the UK economy by £2.9 billion over five years.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644040","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>I refer the hon Member to my previous answer of 26<sup>th</sup> July, UIN 43064.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:54:58.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644040/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644040/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Department for International Trade: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to the Answer of 26 July 2016 to Question 43064, when he plans to publish a list of his special advisers.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644041","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade spoke at a Heritage Foundation lunch during his July visit to the USA. The main topic was the formation of the Department for International Trade and the UK’s priorities on trade and our EU renegotiation.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T17:38:52.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644041/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644041/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Heritage Foundation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether in his meeting with Heritage Foundation staff during his trip to the US in July 2016, he discussed (a) climate change and (b) pharmaceuticals.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644042","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department for International Trade has been engaging widely since the referendum, and has received a number of submissions from trade unions which will inform trade policy development. The Department plans further engagement with trade unions in due course, welcomes submissions and meeting requests at the <a href="mailto:trade.consultation@trade.gsi.gov.uk" target="_blank">trade.consultation@trade.gsi.gov.uk</a> mailbox.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:51:37.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644042/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644042/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Trade Agreements: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what engagement he has had with trade unions on negotiating priorities for the UK's new trading arrangements.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644043","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department for International Trade has not produced any analysis on this issue that extends the work done for the Balance of Competences Review. HM Treasury’s paper on the long term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives refers to studies conducted by other institutions on the impact of rules of origin, but these do not specifically focus on the UK.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:42:41.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644043/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644043/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department has generated any updated estimates of the administrative and compliance costs for British firms linked to rules of origin since the estimates in research published alongside the Balance of Competences Review were produced.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644044","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>As of 25 November, the Department for International Trade had 2709 people working on its agenda, including those deployed overseas. Since 2016 the Department for International Trade (including UK Export Finance) has hired 46 people who had not worked in the civil service previously.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T17:35:18.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644044/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644044/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many officials his Department employs; and what proportion of those officials worked in the Civil Service prior to July 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644045","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government agreed to the provisional application of CETA in October 2016. Provisional application is expected to come into effect in spring 2017. Only provisions within the scope of EU competence will be subject to provisional application.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T18:31:03.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644045/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644045/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644045/answer/previousversion/23511","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the Government agreed to the provisional application in spring 2017 of provisions under exclusive EU competence for the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement during discussions with EU counterparts in October 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644046","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government took part in EU discussions on negotiating lines relating to geographical indicators for the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) in 2011, at which time the Minister of State for Trade and Investment was my noble friend Lord Green of Hurstpierpoint.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-29T17:32:13.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644046/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644046/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which Government Minister represented the UK during EU discussions on its negotiating lines relating to geographical indications on the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644047","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department of International Trade already has a strong and capable trade policy team which has more than doubled in size since 23 June. Over the coming months we will be developing that team to build the world class negotiating strengths needed to deliver the best outcomes for the UK. We will continue to hire the the brightest and best talent from within the UK civil service and look to enhance our team by drawing on expertise from elsewhere.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:46:34.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644047/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644047/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 21 July 2016 to Question 43019, how many civil servants in his Department primarily working on trade policy had prior experience of trade negotiations.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644048","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Department has 191 priority high-value export campaigns for exports, and 250 campaigns for Foreign Direct Investment. At present there are no plans to introduce further campaigns before 31 March 2017. Although the Department will continue to remain responsive to new opportunities to trade around the world as they emerge. The impact of these campaigns will be summarised within the Department’s Annual Report.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-02T14:45:41.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644048/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644048/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-24","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2016 to Question 906161, how many of the priority global high-value export campaigns and campaigns for foreign direct investment are planned to begin before 31 March 2017; and if he will make it his policy to publish regular summaries of the effect of those campaigns.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","54842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644049","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Common Travel Area predates the UK’s and the Republic of Ireland’s membership of the European Union. The UK and Irish Governments are committed to maintaining it and to preserving the rights of Irish and British nationals when in the other State. The Government is working closely with Ireland to consider the implications of the UK’s exit from the EU and to maintain the open borders that UK and Irish citizens enjoy. The focus going forward is on securing a deal that is in the interests of both of the UK and Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-02T14:42:05.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644049/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/644049/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-24","Common Travel Area","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he plans to take to ensure the Common Travel Area is maintained after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","54887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642848","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The information requested is shown in the following tables.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 provides the figures for the year 1 July 2014 – 30 June 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Table 2 provides the cumulative figures from 1 August 1991, after such procedures were brought within a specialist regulatory framework of the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990, to 30 June 2015.</p><p>Table 1</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Live Birth Events</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16886</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Table 2</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Live Birth Events</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>220462</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority.</p><p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority has advised that it does not normally publish recent live birth data so that the figures reported to it may be verified. The information requested, after 30 June 2014, falls into this category and should therefore be treated with caution.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-06T14:16:14.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642848/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642848/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-23","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 22 November (HL3075), how many live births were recorded as a result of those transfers to uteri in the latest year for which records are available, and since August 1991.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642849","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority has advised that the expert panel has sat on four occasions since 2011. Professor Peter Braude has been a member of all four panels.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-05T13:36:54.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642849/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642849/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-23","Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 11 July (HL1098), 7 November (HL2544) and 21 November 2016 (HL3076), when Professor Peter Braude was a member of the expert panel convened by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642850","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>We are aware of reports from pro-regime media outlets of the shelling of a school in al-Furqan (regime-controlled western Aleppo) on 20 November, which resulted in 10 casualties. The attack was alleged to be the responsibility of armed opposition groups. We watched the opposition offensive in western Aleppo closely, and we deplore any breaches of international humanitarian law (IHL) by all parties. We continue to underline to opposition groups over whom we have an influence that any operations must be conducted within the bounds of IHL. The plight of civilians in Aleppo is desperate. The vast majority of atrocities are perpetrated by the regime – it is only the regime and its backers who have the capacity to conduct air strikes, which result in extensive damage to civilian infrastructure and cost civilian lives. 275,000 people face potential mass starvation in east Aleppo, besieged and under daily bombardment by the regime.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-02T14:40:27.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642850/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642850/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-23","Syria: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the identity of those responsible for the death of 10 people, including children, during the bombing of a school in western Aleppo in the third week of November.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL3453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642851","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Social Reform Cabinet Committee has been established by the Prime Minister to consider issues relating to social reform and lead the government’s work to make Britain a country that works for everyone.</p><p> </p><p>This will include taking action to help the most disadvantaged with the focus on tackling the root causes – not the symptoms – of poverty.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-06T14:15:00.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642851/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642851/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-23","Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Social Reform Cabinet Committee is planning to identify and tackle the root causes of poverty; and if not, whether any cross-departmental poverty strategy will be forthcoming.","false","Biography information for Lord Bird",,"Lord Bird","HL3454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642852","Department for Education","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Government received a petition on extending civil partnerships to opposite sex couples from the Equal Civil Partnerships Campaign on 17 November.</p><p>We are currently waiting for a judgment from the Court of Appeal on this matter and are unable to comment whilst legal action is ongoing.</p><p>The Government is committed to equality, and we will provide an update on the Government’s position on civil partnerships once legal proceedings have concluded.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL3456","2016-12-05T17:19:57.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642852/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642852/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-23","Civil Partnerships","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the petition presented to the Minister for Women and Equalities calling for the extension of civil partnerships to different sex couples.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL3455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642853","Department for Education","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Government received a petition on extending civil partnerships to opposite sex couples from the Equal Civil Partnerships Campaign on 17 November.</p><p>We are currently waiting for a judgment from the Court of Appeal on this matter and are unable to comment whilst legal action is ongoing.</p><p>The Government is committed to equality, and we will provide an update on the Government’s position on civil partnerships once legal proceedings have concluded.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL3455","2016-12-05T17:19:57.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642853/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642853/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-23","Civil Partnerships","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to made a decision on the future status of civil partnerships.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL3456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642854","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-07","<p>The borrowing caps were introduced as part of the Housing Revenue Account self-financing settlement, which entailed a once and for all rebalancing of housing debt. There are no plans to lift the caps, which are part of the government's strategy to manage the overall level of public debt.</p><p>Local authorities do have the capacity to borrow to build new homes, there is nearly £3.4 billion headroom available nationally and £2.9 billion in reserves.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-07T15:31:00.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642854/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642854/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-23","Council Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to amend the rules limiting the amount that local authorities can borrow against the value of their existing housing stock; and if so, what is their estimate of the number of houses that local authorities in England could build in the next five years if the limit were removed entirely.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL3457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642855","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>The six cities voluntarily came together as the ‘One North’ group in response to Sir David Higgins’ March 2014 report ‘HS2 Plus’, which recommended that proposals be developed for improved connections between the North’s cities and largest international gateways (ports and airports) to complement High Speed 2.</p><p> </p><p>Subsequently the Transport for the North Partnership Board was established with representation for every local transport authority and Local Enterprise Partnership in the north of England. This body is leading the Northern Powerhouse Rail development programme with the Department for Transport.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-07T12:01:23.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642855/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642855/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-23","Railways: North of England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 22 November (HL3081), what criteria were used to identify the major cities of the north as Manchester, Liverpool, Leeds, Sheffield, Newcastle and Hull; and whether that identification was made by Transport for the North, the Department for Transport, or some other body.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL3458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642856","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government does not hold this information.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-06T14:14:28.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642856/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642856/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-23","Proof of Identity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate (1) of the proportion of persons living in the United Kingdom who do not possess a photo identity document of any kind, or evidence of their address such as a utility bill; and (2) of the number of people who are in consequence unable to open an ordinary bank account.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL3459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642857","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>A small number of trusts are requiring patients to provide identification before they receive treatment.</p><p> </p><p>Care deemed by a clinician to be urgent or immediately necessary must never be withheld until payment is received. Where treatment is considered to be immediately necessary in order to save a patient’s life or to prevent their condition from being life-threatening, treatment must not be delayed or withheld in order to establish their chargeable status.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3461","2016-12-01T15:55:00.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642857/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642857/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-23","NHS: Proof of Identity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which NHS Trusts require patients to provide two forms of identification before they can receive treatment; and whether this applies to persons who attend accident and emergency departments or urgent care units for accident and emergency urgent treatment.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL3460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642858","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>A small number of trusts are requiring patients to provide identification before they receive treatment.</p><p> </p><p>Care deemed by a clinician to be urgent or immediately necessary must never be withheld until payment is received. Where treatment is considered to be immediately necessary in order to save a patient’s life or to prevent their condition from being life-threatening, treatment must not be delayed or withheld in order to establish their chargeable status.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL3460","2016-12-01T15:55:00.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642858/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642858/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-23","NHS: Proof of Identity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many patients have been refused NHS treatment in the past year because they could not provide required proof of identity.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL3461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642860","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>On 23 November the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr. Ellwood), raised with the Israeli Ambassador the concerns expressed in the House of Commons about plans to demolish the Bedouin village of Umm al-Hiran in the Negev. Minister Ellwood also issued a public statement on 23 November, calling on the Israeli authorities and Bedouin community to work together to find a solution that meets the needs and respects the rights of the people affected.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-07T15:08:32.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642860/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642860/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-23","Israel: Bedouin","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about the imminent demolition of the Bedouin village of Umm al-Hiran.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL3462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642861","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>No elected representative should have their security threatened. Councillors are volunteers and community champions. It is for political parties to encourage individuals to stand as their candidates for elected office, both locally and nationally.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-06T14:24:59.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642861/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642861/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-23","Demonstrations: Hounslow","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they will take to ensure that the decision of the Crown Prosecution Service not to prosecute in relation to a demonstration outside the home of the Leader of the London Borough of Hounslow does not adversely impact on the willingness of members of the public to stand for elected office, both locally and nationally.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL3463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642862","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is supporting a £28,000 needs assessment, through its Bilateral Programme Fund, on the prospects for oil and gas exploration in Malawi. This will highlight the potential environmental impact as well as the various economic, legislative, social and political factors. Any decision on the potential future exploitation of oil and gas reserves will be for the Government of Malawi to decide. All parties, including the Department for International Development and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, want to ensure that any exploration is done in a sustainable and environmentally friendly way. Exploring such opportunities will help eradicate poverty, create jobs, increase revenue and reduce dependency on aid. This, and any future UK Government spending, will be firmly in the interests of Malawi.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-02T14:41:39.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642862/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642862/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-23","Malawi: Prosperity Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Foreign and Commonwealth Office spent £30,000 from the Prosperity Fund on a project supporting the government of Malawi in developing the country’s oil and gas sector; and how they intend to ensure that future spending from the Prosperity Fund in Malawi meets the stated aim of promoting economic reform and development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642863","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-05","<p>HM Revenue and Customs published a consultation document setting out the Government’s proposals on 15 August 2015 entitled “Making Tax Digital: Bringing business tax into the digital age”. The consultation included an initial assessment of the impacts on businesses. The consultation closed on 7 November. The government is currently considering the responses to the Making Tax Digital consultations and will publish its response and draft legislation in January, together with an updated Tax Impact Assessment.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-12-05T16:37:28.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642863/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642863/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-23","Small Businesses: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the fact that most small businesses assess their profits annually in arrears, whether it is the intention of HM Revenue and Customs to make small businesses report their income and expenditure quarterly; and what assessment they have made of the feasibility of this requirement.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL3465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642864","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is absolutely committed to looking after the mental health of our Armed Forces, and provides a range of community-based health care in line with national best practice. We appreciate that personnel with mental health issues might need access to help outside normal working hours, and we provide this by working in close partnership with a variety of different organisations, including the NHS and Service charities.</p><p> </p><p>In most areas of the UK, immediate out of hours care includes the free 24-hour mental health helpline run by the charity Combat Stress (which receives funding from MOD), and the Big White Wall, a 24-hour online community. In Northern Ireland, we provide MOD-managed telephone support for Service personnel for primary healthcare, as there is no contracted independent service provider for this type of health care in that part of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>In the most serious cases, where urgent treatment is required, we are able to arrange emergency admittance to one of eight specialised inpatient NHS mental health units, under a contract between MOD and a consortium of NHS Trusts. These units have a range of dedicated facilities for military personnel, and admission can be arranged at any time of day or night.</p><p> </p><p>We believe that these arrangements are robust and effective, and there are therefore no plans to provide an additional helpline.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-11-29T17:03:35.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642864/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642864/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-23","Armed Forces: Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to provide a dedicated 24-hour mental health helpline for serving soldiers.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642865","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-30","<p>The Ministry of Defence takes the mental health and well-being of its personnel very seriously. Our policy aims to reduce suicide risk through education, tackling stigma, and providing rapid, easily accessible, and flexible access to mental health support and health care services.</p><p>For the period 1 August 2002 to 31 December 2015, the rate of coroner confirmed suicides and open verdict deaths amongst those who had previously deployed to either Iraq or Afghanistan and were still in Service at the time of their death was 0.9 per 1,000. This compared to a rate of 1.6 per 1,000 for those UK service personnel who have not been identified as having deployed to either Iraq or Afghanistan prior to their death.</p><p>The 'Suicide and Open Verdict Deaths in the UK Regular Armed Forces 1984-2015' National Statistics Notice published in March 2016 shows that over the past 30 years, male suicide rates among the UK regular Armed Forces have been lower than the UK general population. In 2014, the male suicide rate in the UK general population was 16.8 per 100,000 compared to a UK Armed Forces rate of 4 per 100,000.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-11-30T16:29:04.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642865/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642865/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-23","Armed Forces: Suicide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the rate of suicide among UK armed forces personnel who have seen active service in Afghanistan or Iraq.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642866","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>The information requested for the latest 12 months available is published in table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1) in ‘Immigration Statistics, April - June 2016’, available from the GOV.UK website.</p><p>In the year ending June 2016, there were 2,866,872 entry clearance visa applications (including visitors and those on transit visas). Over the same period there were 2,457,977 grants. These figures include main applicants and dependants.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3469","2016-12-12T17:14:05.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642866/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642866/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Entry Clearances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many entry clearance visa applications have been received in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642867","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>The information requested for the latest 12 months available is published in table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1) in ‘Immigration Statistics, April - June 2016’, available from the GOV.UK website.</p><p>In the year ending June 2016, there were 2,866,872 entry clearance visa applications (including visitors and those on transit visas). Over the same period there were 2,457,977 grants. These figures include main applicants and dependants.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3468","2016-12-12T17:14:05.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642867/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642867/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Entry Clearances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many entry clearance visas have been granted in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642868","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-29","<p>There were 2,190 recipients of the UK State Pension who were resident overseas with non-uprated State Pensions on 31<sup>st</sup> May 2015 and who were resident in the UK on 31<sup>st</sup> May 2016.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source: DWP Work and Pensions Longitudinal Study 100% data.</em></p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li><em>Figures are rounded to the nearest 10. </em></li><li><em>The administrative data on State Pension represents snapshots of information. To answer the question two snapshots of data have been compared but there could have been additional movements of residency during this time that would not be captured – for example if someone moved back to the UK but then left again before 31<sup>st</sup> May 2016.</em></li></ol>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-11-29T12:35:02.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642868/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642868/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-23","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many UK pensioners whose pensions are frozen because they live overseas have moved back to the UK in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642869","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>Police stop and search powers are provided for within the following Sections of the Terrorism Act (2000): 43 (search of persons), 43a (search of vehicles) and 47a (authorisations to search persons and vehicles without suspicion within a specified area).</p><p>Searching of persons and vehicles without suspicion has not been used by police forces in Great Britain since March 2011 and the Home Office does not collate or collect data on vehicle searches. The Home Office collects data on searches of persons from the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS). The number of people arrested by the MPS following stop and search was:</p><p>• 23 in the year 1 July 2013 to 30 June 2014;</p><p>• 33 in the year 1 July 2014 to 30 June 2015; and</p><p>• 64 in the year to 1 July 2015 to 30 June 2016.</p><p>Further information can be found in the Home Office Quarterly Statistical Bulletin, including data relating to stop and search powers. The most recent was published on 22 September 2016. It can be found at: www.gov.uk/government/collection/counter-terrorism-statistics.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-12T17:29:43.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642869/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642869/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Terrorism: Stop and Search","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many arrests have been made as a result of the exercise of powers to stop and search under the Terrorism Act 2006 in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642870","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>There are provisions relating to price transparency, metering and billing of district heating networks in the Heat Network (Metering and Billing) Regulations 2014. There is also a requirement for energy costs to be provided in a format which enables customers to compare the charges of different energy suppliers. A voluntary code called HeatTrust was established last year by the industry trade association, with the support of Government, to improve customer protection in this sector. HeatTrust has recently launched an on-line price comparator tool for heat network customers.</p><p>Heat network customers are covered by general consumer protection, competition and contract law as well as tenancy law where relevant.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-01T17:17:48.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642870/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642870/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-23","District Heating","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consumer protection exists in relation to energy pricing for customers of district heating networks.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL3472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642871","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>Ofgem is responsible for the regulation of the gas and electricity markets. Its remit does not cover district heating networks or protection for heat network customers.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-01T17:18:05.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642871/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642871/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-23","District Heating","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what responsibilities Ofgem has in relation to consumer protection for customers of district heating networks.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL3473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642872","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>At present, there are no plans for the government to conduct a formal review into competition between, and pricing of, the heat network industry. The Government monitors these issues as part of its implementation of the Heat Network Investment Project and the development of the market more generally.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-01T17:16:36.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642872/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642872/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-23","District Heating","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to conduct a review into competition between, and pricing of, district heating networks.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL3474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642873","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-28","<p>Data is published by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on switching. The data is collected by Ofgem and republished by BEIS in Table 2.7.1 of which can be found online (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/quarterly-domestic-energy-switching-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/quarterly-domestic-energy-switching-statistics</a> ). Multiple switches made by the same customer in each year are counted as separate switches.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of electricity switches</p></td><td><p>Number of gas switches</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4,206,000</p></td><td><p>3,270,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3,342,000</p></td><td><p>2,280,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>3,425,000</p></td><td><p>2,190,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3,058,000</p></td><td><p>2,281,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>3,396,000</p></td><td><p>2,709,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-11-28T16:14:58.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642873/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642873/answer","table_271.xls","Quarterly domestic energy switching statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642873/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-23","Energy: Competition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many customers have switched their energy provider in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL3475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642874","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>While the UK remains a member of the EU, EU nationals continue to enjoy rights of free movement in accordance with the UK’s Treaty obligations, and employers in the horticultural sector can continue to recruit EU workers to meet seasonal labour needs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:55:33.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642874/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642874/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Migrant Workers: Agriculture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 15 November (HL3019), whether they will consider implementing a new Seasonal Agricultural Permit Scheme that allows non-EU workers to work in the UK for a set period of less than 12 months to fill temporary jobs in commercial fruit and vegetable production.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL3476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642875","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-05","<p>The UK’s current production to supply ratio is 76% for indigenous-type foods and 61% for all foods. This has remained steady over the last decade and is not low in the context of the last 150 years.</p><p>Global food security is dependent on a number of factors including increasing production sustainably, reducing waste and ensuring open markets around the world to facilitate trade.</p><p>The Government remains committed to publishing a 25 Year Food and Farming Plan. The Plan aims to increase the competitiveness and productivity of British producers, enabling them to compete more effectively in domestic and overseas markets.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-12-05T12:23:28.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642875/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642875/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-23","Food: Self-sufficiency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the UK is self-sufficient in staple foodstuffs; and if not, whether they plan to make the UK self-sufficient.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL3477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642876","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-08","<p>This Government is committed to promoting UK exports of goods and services, to support a growing economy that creates wealth for all, supports jobs and meets our wider national interests. The Department for International Trade is working to deliver the best international trading framework for the UK to maximise global trade and investment opportunities.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-12-08T12:27:35.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642876/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642876/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-23","Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to follow a policy of export substitution.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL3478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642877","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Details on the naming of storms over the UK and Ireland, together with all the latest information about storms in the UK, are available on the Met Office website at <a href="http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/barometer/uk-storm-centre" target="_blank">http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/barometer/uk-storm-centre</a>.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-06T12:11:53.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642877/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642877/answer","met-office-naming-storms.pdf","Details on the naming of storms","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642877/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-23","Storms","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they are planning to publicise and explain the new arrangement for naming storms over the UK and Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL3479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642878","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Immigration Act states that we will transfer unaccompanied refugee children. Our criteria under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 are intended to ensure that we are focusing on the most vulnerable children. In France, we will be considering those aged 12 and under of any nationality, children referred to us by the French authorities as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation of any nationality, and those nationalities most likely to qualify for refugee status in the UK, aged 15 and below.</p><p>All unaccompanied asylum seeking children with close family in the UK will continue to be considered for transfer under the criteria set out in the Dublin Regulation, regardless of age or nationality. Between 1 January and 1 October 2016, over 140 unaccompanied asylum seeking children were accepted for transfer under the Dublin Regulation, compared to around 20 children in the whole of 2015. Eurostat, the EU’s statistics agency, regularly publishes Member State figures for Dublin transfers.</p><p>Furthermore, since 10 October, we have transferred over 300 unaccompanied minors to the UK from France. This includes over 80 girls, many of whom were identified as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation; and more than 200 unaccompanied asylum seeking children with close family links to the UK under the Dublin Regulation. The Home Secretary told Parliament on 24 October that several hundred more children and young people will be brought to the UK in the coming days and weeks.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3481 ; HL3482","2016-12-06T17:09:10.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642878/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642878/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what criteria they have applied to the assessment of unaccompanied refugee children from the Calais camp.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL3480"
