nment how many children have been admitted to the UK under the Dublin III Regulation; and how many applications remain outstanding.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL3481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642880","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Immigration Act states that we will transfer unaccompanied refugee children. Our criteria under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 are intended to ensure that we are focusing on the most vulnerable children. In France, we will be considering those aged 12 and under of any nationality, children referred to us by the French authorities as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation of any nationality, and those nationalities most likely to qualify for refugee status in the UK, aged 15 and below.</p><p>All unaccompanied asylum seeking children with close family in the UK will continue to be considered for transfer under the criteria set out in the Dublin Regulation, regardless of age or nationality. Between 1 January and 1 October 2016, over 140 unaccompanied asylum seeking children were accepted for transfer under the Dublin Regulation, compared to around 20 children in the whole of 2015. Eurostat, the EU’s statistics agency, regularly publishes Member State figures for Dublin transfers.</p><p>Furthermore, since 10 October, we have transferred over 300 unaccompanied minors to the UK from France. This includes over 80 girls, many of whom were identified as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation; and more than 200 unaccompanied asylum seeking children with close family links to the UK under the Dublin Regulation. The Home Secretary told Parliament on 24 October that several hundred more children and young people will be brought to the UK in the coming days and weeks.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3480 ; HL3481","2016-12-06T17:09:10.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642880/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642880/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many children have been admitted to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016; and how many applications are still outstanding.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL3482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642881","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>As set out by Health Education England in its <em>Workforce Plan for England: Proposed Education and Training Commissions for 2016/2017</em>, an increase in available supply of between 3,000 and 40,000 nurses (adult, children’s, mental health and learning disability nurses) is forecast by 2020 compared with 2015. A copy of the Plan is attached.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been made of how many of these nurses will choose to be employed by agencies. However the Government’s agency controls are already moving staff back to substantive and bank roles.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-06T15:27:41.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642881/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642881/answer","HEE Workforce Plan for England 2016 180516_0.pdf","HEE Workforce Plan For England","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642881/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-23","Nurses: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 22 November (HL Deb, cols 1831–2), how many of the additional 40,000 nurses will be employed by agencies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL3483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642882","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Department does not hold national data on agency staff that is broken down by this staff group.</p><p> </p><p>Each trust publishes financial accounts which are publically available. Trusts are responsible for collecting the appropriate level of information on their agency spending that will enable them to achieve maximum value for money.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-07T15:29:50.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642882/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642882/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-23","Agency Nurses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 22 November (HL Deb, cols 1831–2), what percentage of the NHS nursing budget was spent on agency staff in the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL3484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642883","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>The review of citizenship is ongoing.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-07T15:35:25.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642883/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642883/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","British Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 25 April and 10 May (HL7517 and HL8199), what progress has been made on the review of British nationality law and citizenship; whether the date for the consultation has now been finalised; and if so, when the details will be published.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL3485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642884","Department for Education","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Department for Education intends to publish the questionnaire from the first Children’s Services Omnibus Survey in Spring 2017, as part of the research report. This is standard practice for research reports. There are no plans to publish the questionnaire prior to this.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-07T17:56:39.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642884/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642884/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-23","Children: Social Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Nash on 16 November (HL3148), whether they will publish the questionnaire used in the Children's Services Omnibus Survey before they publish the research report.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL3486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642885","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government monitors implementation of its policy commitments rather than individual legislative measures. This Government has inherited responsibility for an extensive statute book which dates back to the 13th Century. It is Government policy only to legislate where legislation is required to deliver a policy. Where possible the Government will seek to repeal redundant laws and support the work of the law commissions.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-06T14:27:30.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642885/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642885/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-23","Legislation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to review the extent and number of legislative provisions that have never been commenced and the implications of leaving such provisions on the statute book.","false","Biography information for Lord Norton of Louth",,"Lord Norton of Louth","HL3487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642887","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the Government’s previous answer of 15 June 2016 [HL465]: the requirement of section 3(6) of the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act is set out in the Civil Service Code, which forms part of the contract of employment for all civil servants.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-06T14:10:31.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642887/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642887/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-23","Civil Servants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what checks have taken place to ensure that government departments are compliant with section 3(6) of the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act 2010, which states that civil servants who advise Ministers should be aware of the constitutional significance of Parliament and of the conventions governing the relationship between Parliament and Her Majesty's Government.","false","Biography information for Lord Norton of Louth",,"Lord Norton of Louth","HL3488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642888","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>Aside from the information included in my Written Answer of 15 November (HL2957) regarding British Gibraltar Territorial Waters, the Government does not hold comprehensive records on British State vessels entering into Spanish Territorial Waters or Spanish State vessels entering into British Territorial Waters.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-07T15:08:54.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642888/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642888/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-23","Spain: Territorial Waters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 15 November (HL2957), what were (1) the number of incursions by British State vessels into Spanish Territorial waters, and (2) the number of incursions by Spanish State vessels into British Territorial waters around the whole British Isles, in the same period.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL3489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642889","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>All applications are considered on their individual merits and in line with the Immigration Rules. In order to safeguard an individual’s personal information and comply with the Data Protection Act 1998 the Home Office does not routinely comment on individual cases.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:52:14.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642889/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642889/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Visas: Iraq","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on what grounds visas were denied to Syrian Orthodox bishops, Bishop Nicodemus Dawad, bishop of Mosul, and Bishop Timotheus Moussa, bishop of the Monastery of St Matthew, who were invited to the consecration of the new UK Syrian Orthodox cathedral in the presence of His Royal Highness the Prince of Wales.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL3490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642890","Home Office","false","2017-01-18","<p>I am sorry but the Home Office does not hold this information.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-18T17:30:52.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642890/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642890/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Ivory: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many successful prosecutions have been made in respect of the sale of ivory in the UK under the Control of Trade in Endangered Species (Enforcement) Regulations 1997.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL3491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642891","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>With the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, the Home Office funds the National Wildlife Crime Unit, which provides intelligence, analysis and specialist assistance to individual police forces and other law enforcement agencies in the United Kingdom that allows them to deal effectively with wildlife crime investigations, including cases that involve the illegal trading of ivory.</p><p>The Unit will provide briefing notes for all UK police forces with regards to the enforcement of any changes arising from the Government’s plans to ban the sale of any post-1947 worked ivory. The police may also receive expert advice about ivory from organisations such as the Animal and Plant Health Agency and the Joint Nature Conservation Committee. Police and NCA are given appropriate training as their deployment requires.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-21T12:46:07.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642891/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642891/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Ivory: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what further training they intend to provide to the police and the National Crime Agency in preparation for their plan for a complete ban on the sale of ivory.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL3492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642892","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Review of the Use and Retention of Custody Images will set out how such images are used. We plan to publish the review shortly.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:45:54.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642892/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642892/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the recommendations of the 8th Annual Report of the National DNA Database Ethics Group, what plans they have to inform the public of both the implicit and explicit possibilities for the use of custody images prior to seeking feedback from the public on the storage by police of facial images.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642893","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Review of the Use and Retention of Custody Images will be published shortly.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T14:02:22.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642893/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642893/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will publish the 2015 Home Office review of custody images.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642894","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Review of the Use and Retention of Custody Images will make recommendations in relation to the use and retention of custody images to policing.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:49:11.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642894/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642894/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will issue guidance on the use and storage of custody images in the light of the findings by the 8th Annual Report of the National DNA Database Ethics Group that some police "retain custody images indefinitely or until the subject requests for them to be deleted".","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642895","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>We acknowledge these privacy concerns, and will address them in the Review of the Use and Retention of Custody Images.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:47:34.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642895/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642895/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the finding by the 8th Report of the National DNA Ethics Group that the storing and searching of facial images by police forces are likely to raise significant concerns with regard to privacy.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642896","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>With respect to the views expressed in the report, the justification is that a custody image taken on arrest can be retained for legitimate policing purposes under Paragraph 5 of the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:46:46.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642896/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642896/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they plan to take in response to the view expressed in the 8th Report of the National DNA Ethics Group that a clear distinction needs to be made between the taking of custody images for a specified purpose, and the retention and use of that image for other purposes than originally intended and for which consent has not been given.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642897","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>With respect to the findings in the report, we do not plan to stop the retention and use of custody images. These images are used by the police to obtain leads during investigations, but would only be one factor in these investigations.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-06T17:46:22.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642897/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642897/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to stop the use and retention of facial images by police forces in the light of the findings in the 8th Report of the National DNA Ethics Group of the propensity for errors in the use of digital searches of custody images, and the potential for these searches to result in mistaken identity and the wrongful inclusion of an individual in the early stages of a police investigation.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642898","Home Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>We will specify in due course the number of unaccompanied refugee children to be transferred to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p><p>The Immigration Act states that we will relocate unaccompanied refugee children. Our criteria under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 are intended to ensure that we are focusing on the most vulnerable children. In France, we will be considering those aged 12 and under of any nationality, children referred to us by the French authorities as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation of any nationality, and those nationalities most likely to qualify for refugee status in the UK, aged 15 and below. The criteria for relocating children to the UK from France, under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, are based on the reasonable likelihood of their qualifying for refugee status and achieving long-term stability. The criteria are therefore in line with the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child.</p><p>The guarantee of rights in relation to children, and the delivery of appropriate services to individual children, is currently provided by the French State. Our policies do not deprive any child of access to these benefits and therefore are fully in line with the UN Convention of the Rights of the Child. Furthermore, Section 55 of the Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009 requires the Secretary of State to carry out their immigration and asylum functions in a way that takes into account the need to safeguard and promote the welfare of children in the UK. Where a child is outside the UK, the spirit of the duty should be applied. Social workers, rather than Home Office staff, are carrying out best interest determinations in France.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL3500 ; HL3501 ; HL3502 ; HL3503","2016-12-05T17:57:12.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642898/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/642898/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-23","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will provide a definitive figure for the total number of unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to be transferred to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3499"
